Dialogue: 0,0:00:22.05,0:00:23.82,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Hey everyone, I'm Joe Cerra
Dialogue: 0,0:00:23.82,0:00:26.47,Default,,0,0,0,,and I'm an engineer UIKit and
Dialogue: 0,0:00:26.47,0:00:28.42,Default,,0,0,0,,welcome to advanced animations
Dialogue: 0,0:00:28.42,0:00:29.15,Default,,0,0,0,,with UIKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:29.25,0:00:32.25,Default,,0,0,0,,So, today we have a lot to talk
Dialogue: 0,0:00:32.25,0:00:32.55,Default,,0,0,0,,about.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:32.86,0:00:33.83,Default,,0,0,0,,We're going to start off by
Dialogue: 0,0:00:33.83,0:00:35.54,Default,,0,0,0,,covering some of the basics and
Dialogue: 0,0:00:35.54,0:00:37.58,Default,,0,0,0,,how animations work and also how
Dialogue: 0,0:00:37.58,0:00:38.60,Default,,0,0,0,,animations are timed.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:40.13,0:00:41.29,Default,,0,0,0,,We're going to discuss how to
Dialogue: 0,0:00:41.29,0:00:42.50,Default,,0,0,0,,make animations fully
Dialogue: 0,0:00:42.50,0:00:43.76,Default,,0,0,0,,interactive and interruptible
Dialogue: 0,0:00:43.76,0:00:45.86,Default,,0,0,0,,using some modern techniques.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:46.50,0:00:48.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Then we're going to talk about
Dialogue: 0,0:00:48.01,0:00:49.02,Default,,0,0,0,,some of the new API that we're
Dialogue: 0,0:00:49.02,0:00:50.53,Default,,0,0,0,,providing this year in iOS 11.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.53,0:00:52.97,Default,,0,0,0,,And then we're going to use all
Dialogue: 0,0:00:52.97,0:00:54.18,Default,,0,0,0,,of that knowledge and I'm going
Dialogue: 0,0:00:54.18,0:00:55.63,Default,,0,0,0,,to show you how to coordinate
Dialogue: 0,0:00:55.63,0:00:56.19,Default,,0,0,0,,animations.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:57.34,0:00:58.95,Default,,0,0,0,,And then finally, we're going to
Dialogue: 0,0:00:58.95,0:01:00.83,Default,,0,0,0,,go over some tips and tricks and
Dialogue: 0,0:01:00.83,0:01:02.12,Default,,0,0,0,,a few more techniques to help
Dialogue: 0,0:01:02.12,0:01:03.01,Default,,0,0,0,,you create really great
Dialogue: 0,0:01:03.01,0:01:04.16,Default,,0,0,0,,animations for your users.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:05.77,0:01:06.81,Default,,0,0,0,,So, let's get into it.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:08.44,0:01:09.93,Default,,0,0,0,,UIView-based animations have
Dialogue: 0,0:01:09.93,0:01:10.96,Default,,0,0,0,,been around really since the
Dialogue: 0,0:01:10.96,0:01:11.72,Default,,0,0,0,,dawn of iOS.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:11.72,0:01:13.57,Default,,0,0,0,,And here's a quick refresher on
Dialogue: 0,0:01:13.57,0:01:14.12,Default,,0,0,0,,how they work.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:15.46,0:01:16.68,Default,,0,0,0,,So, say I have a UIView that
Dialogue: 0,0:01:16.68,0:01:17.98,Default,,0,0,0,,renders a circle and I'd like
Dialogue: 0,0:01:17.98,0:01:20.18,Default,,0,0,0,,the animate it from its position
Dialogue: 0,0:01:20.18,0:01:21.57,Default,,0,0,0,,of X equals zero to 100.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:21.77,0:01:24.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Well the way I might do this is
Dialogue: 0,0:01:24.14,0:01:25.51,Default,,0,0,0,,by calling the UIView.animate
Dialogue: 0,0:01:25.51,0:01:25.85,Default,,0,0,0,,method.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:26.57,0:01:28.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Here I'm calling UIView.animate
Dialogue: 0,0:01:28.09,0:01:30.13,Default,,0,0,0,,with a duration, performing some
Dialogue: 0,0:01:30.13,0:01:31.27,Default,,0,0,0,,animations in an animation
Dialogue: 0,0:01:31.27,0:01:31.58,Default,,0,0,0,,block.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:31.99,0:01:33.24,Default,,0,0,0,,In this case, I'm offsetting the
Dialogue: 0,0:01:33.24,0:01:35.47,Default,,0,0,0,,X value of our circle by 100.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:36.47,0:01:38.33,Default,,0,0,0,,And when I do that UIKit will
Dialogue: 0,0:01:38.33,0:01:39.78,Default,,0,0,0,,implicitly create an animation,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:39.78,0:01:41.12,Default,,0,0,0,,add it to our layer and produce
Dialogue: 0,0:01:41.15,0:01:42.14,Default,,0,0,0,,the following animation.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:44.32,0:01:46.29,Default,,0,0,0,,But last year we introduced the
Dialogue: 0,0:01:46.29,0:01:48.23,Default,,0,0,0,,UIViewPropertyAnimator, which
Dialogue: 0,0:01:48.23,0:01:49.94,Default,,0,0,0,,gives us a lot more control for
Dialogue: 0,0:01:49.94,0:01:51.74,Default,,0,0,0,,animations than its predecessor
Dialogue: 0,0:01:51.74,0:01:52.59,Default,,0,0,0,,UIViewAnimate.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:53.13,0:01:55.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Now this includes being able to
Dialogue: 0,0:01:55.33,0:01:57.15,Default,,0,0,0,,provide custom timing functions
Dialogue: 0,0:01:57.42,0:01:58.29,Default,,0,0,0,,and the ability to make your
Dialogue: 0,0:01:58.29,0:01:59.90,Default,,0,0,0,,animations fully interactive and
Dialogue: 0,0:01:59.90,0:02:01.50,Default,,0,0,0,,interruptible really easily.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:02.47,0:02:03.91,Default,,0,0,0,,In fact, with property animator
Dialogue: 0,0:02:04.53,0:02:05.90,Default,,0,0,0,,you can modify your animations
Dialogue: 0,0:02:05.90,0:02:06.54,Default,,0,0,0,,on the fly.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:07.93,0:02:08.60,Default,,0,0,0,,So, let's take a look at our
Dialogue: 0,0:02:08.60,0:02:09.61,Default,,0,0,0,,animation again and this time
Dialogue: 0,0:02:09.61,0:02:11.00,Default,,0,0,0,,we're going to use an animator
Dialogue: 0,0:02:11.00,0:02:12.46,Default,,0,0,0,,to animate it.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:12.46,0:02:13.44,Default,,0,0,0,,So, we create our animator
Dialogue: 0,0:02:13.53,0:02:14.56,Default,,0,0,0,,providing a duration and a
Dialogue: 0,0:02:14.56,0:02:16.31,Default,,0,0,0,,timing curve provider
Dialogue: 0,0:02:16.31,0:02:16.93,Default,,0,0,0,,animations.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.54,0:02:19.00,Default,,0,0,0,,And then we call startAnimator
Dialogue: 0,0:02:19.16,0:02:20.62,Default,,0,0,0,,which actually then runs that
Dialogue: 0,0:02:20.62,0:02:22.31,Default,,0,0,0,,animation block producing this
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.31,0:02:22.80,Default,,0,0,0,,animation.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:27.08,0:02:28.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Now in the last two examples we
Dialogue: 0,0:02:28.37,0:02:29.82,Default,,0,0,0,,drove our animation with a
Dialogue: 0,0:02:29.82,0:02:30.99,Default,,0,0,0,,linear timing curve.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:31.64,0:02:33.32,Default,,0,0,0,,And what a timing curve is, is
Dialogue: 0,0:02:33.32,0:02:34.81,Default,,0,0,0,,essentially a function that maps
Dialogue: 0,0:02:34.96,0:02:37.40,Default,,0,0,0,,time to progress or the fraction
Dialogue: 0,0:02:37.40,0:02:38.81,Default,,0,0,0,,of elapsed time of your
Dialogue: 0,0:02:38.81,0:02:40.61,Default,,0,0,0,,animation to the fraction of
Dialogue: 0,0:02:40.66,0:02:41.79,Default,,0,0,0,,progress of your animation.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:43.15,0:02:44.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Now linear timing curves are
Dialogue: 0,0:02:44.24,0:02:46.23,Default,,0,0,0,,actually kind of interesting and
Dialogue: 0,0:02:46.26,0:02:47.83,Default,,0,0,0,,this is because the fraction of
Dialogue: 0,0:02:47.92,0:02:49.34,Default,,0,0,0,,time is equal to the fraction of
Dialogue: 0,0:02:49.37,0:02:51.04,Default,,0,0,0,,progress and we'll see why this
Dialogue: 0,0:02:51.04,0:02:53.90,Default,,0,0,0,,is interesting in just a second.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:54.29,0:02:56.03,Default,,0,0,0,,There are also of course, timing
Dialogue: 0,0:02:56.03,0:02:57.82,Default,,0,0,0,,curves other than linear, such
Dialogue: 0,0:02:57.82,0:02:59.45,Default,,0,0,0,,as the built-in ease in timing
Dialogue: 0,0:02:59.45,0:03:01.08,Default,,0,0,0,,function which starts off slowly
Dialogue: 0,0:03:01.08,0:03:02.01,Default,,0,0,0,,and then accelerates.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:02.76,0:03:04.43,Default,,0,0,0,,And the built-in ease out timing
Dialogue: 0,0:03:04.43,0:03:05.35,Default,,0,0,0,,function which starts off
Dialogue: 0,0:03:05.39,0:03:06.66,Default,,0,0,0,,quickly and then decelerates.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:07.64,0:03:09.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Well with property animators you
Dialogue: 0,0:03:09.35,0:03:10.42,Default,,0,0,0,,can provide your own custom
Dialogue: 0,0:03:10.42,0:03:11.88,Default,,0,0,0,,timing functions, such as this
Dialogue: 0,0:03:11.88,0:03:12.06,Default,,0,0,0,,one.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:12.77,0:03:14.16,Default,,0,0,0,,And the way you do that is by
Dialogue: 0,0:03:14.16,0:03:15.74,Default,,0,0,0,,providing two cubic Bezier
Dialogue: 0,0:03:15.74,0:03:16.35,Default,,0,0,0,,control points.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:17.69,0:03:19.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Now we'll see a little bit later
Dialogue: 0,0:03:19.47,0:03:21.69,Default,,0,0,0,,why it can be really useful to
Dialogue: 0,0:03:21.69,0:03:22.65,Default,,0,0,0,,be able to provide your own
Dialogue: 0,0:03:22.65,0:03:23.67,Default,,0,0,0,,custom timing functions.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:25.77,0:03:27.20,Default,,0,0,0,,So that's essentially how
Dialogue: 0,0:03:27.20,0:03:27.99,Default,,0,0,0,,animations work.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:29.12,0:03:30.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Now I want to talk about how to
Dialogue: 0,0:03:30.26,0:03:31.58,Default,,0,0,0,,make your animations fully
Dialogue: 0,0:03:31.58,0:03:32.15,Default,,0,0,0,,interactive.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:33.77,0:03:35.31,Default,,0,0,0,,So, an interactive animation is
Dialogue: 0,0:03:35.31,0:03:36.92,Default,,0,0,0,,one in which the user's actions
Dialogue: 0,0:03:36.96,0:03:38.95,Default,,0,0,0,,interactively drive the progress
Dialogue: 0,0:03:38.95,0:03:39.68,Default,,0,0,0,,of your animation.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:40.65,0:03:41.72,Default,,0,0,0,,So, here's a familiar example
Dialogue: 0,0:03:41.72,0:03:43.13,Default,,0,0,0,,where a gesture is driving
Dialogue: 0,0:03:43.13,0:03:44.53,Default,,0,0,0,,interactive animation and now
Dialogue: 0,0:03:44.53,0:03:46.65,Default,,0,0,0,,we're using 3D Touch to drive
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.65,0:03:47.56,Default,,0,0,0,,another animation.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:48.09,0:03:50.79,Default,,0,0,0,,And we can, of course, dismiss
Dialogue: 0,0:03:50.79,0:03:51.76,Default,,0,0,0,,our Control Center view
Dialogue: 0,0:03:51.76,0:03:53.08,Default,,0,0,0,,interactively with a gesture.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:54.65,0:03:55.39,Default,,0,0,0,,So, let's do a quick
Dialogue: 0,0:03:55.59,0:03:56.40,Default,,0,0,0,,demonstration here.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:56.98,0:03:58.60,Default,,0,0,0,,So, we're going to add a
Dialogue: 0,0:03:58.60,0:03:59.76,Default,,0,0,0,,PanGestureRecognizer to our
Dialogue: 0,0:03:59.76,0:04:02.23,Default,,0,0,0,,circle and we're going to
Dialogue: 0,0:04:02.23,0:04:03.63,Default,,0,0,0,,animate it, but we're going to
Dialogue: 0,0:04:03.63,0:04:04.80,Default,,0,0,0,,do so with our finger by
Dialogue: 0,0:04:04.80,0:04:05.71,Default,,0,0,0,,scrubbing an animator.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:05.71,0:04:07.39,Default,,0,0,0,,And at this point we're going to
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.39,0:04:08.76,Default,,0,0,0,,lift our finger off and continue
Dialogue: 0,0:04:08.76,0:04:09.97,Default,,0,0,0,,that animation to its target
Dialogue: 0,0:04:09.97,0:04:10.38,Default,,0,0,0,,position.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:10.38,0:04:13.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Now here's the code to do this.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:14.46,0:04:17.25,Default,,0,0,0,,We're going to save an instance
Dialogue: 0,0:04:17.25,0:04:19.09,Default,,0,0,0,,of our property animator in our
Dialogue: 0,0:04:19.15,0:04:20.65,Default,,0,0,0,,hand gesture recognizer handler.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:21.12,0:04:22.39,Default,,0,0,0,,We're going to create that
Dialogue: 0,0:04:22.39,0:04:23.82,Default,,0,0,0,,animator and initialize it with
Dialogue: 0,0:04:23.87,0:04:25.54,Default,,0,0,0,,some animations in an ease out
Dialogue: 0,0:04:25.54,0:04:25.98,Default,,0,0,0,,timing function.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:30.12,0:04:31.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Afterwards we're going to call
Dialogue: 0,0:04:31.38,0:04:33.08,Default,,0,0,0,,pauseAnimation immediately after
Dialogue: 0,0:04:33.14,0:04:34.06,Default,,0,0,0,,and that's going to run that
Dialogue: 0,0:04:34.06,0:04:35.60,Default,,0,0,0,,animation block producing that
Dialogue: 0,0:04:35.60,0:04:36.78,Default,,0,0,0,,animation implicitly.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:37.56,0:04:39.03,Default,,0,0,0,,And what property animator does
Dialogue: 0,0:04:39.16,0:04:41.06,Default,,0,0,0,,is essentially sets the speed of
Dialogue: 0,0:04:41.06,0:04:42.41,Default,,0,0,0,,that animation to zero.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:43.01,0:04:44.64,Default,,0,0,0,,So now we can interact with it.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.18,0:04:46.33,Default,,0,0,0,,So, we're going to scrub our
Dialogue: 0,0:04:46.33,0:04:47.58,Default,,0,0,0,,animator's fraction complete
Dialogue: 0,0:04:47.70,0:04:48.91,Default,,0,0,0,,based on the distance our finger
Dialogue: 0,0:04:48.91,0:04:50.63,Default,,0,0,0,,travels relative to the total
Dialogue: 0,0:04:50.63,0:04:52.34,Default,,0,0,0,,distance of the animation, which
Dialogue: 0,0:04:52.34,0:04:53.94,Default,,0,0,0,,in this case is 100 because
Dialogue: 0,0:04:53.94,0:04:55.08,Default,,0,0,0,,we're animating from zero to
Dialogue: 0,0:04:55.08,0:04:55.43,Default,,0,0,0,,100.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:57.67,0:04:58.77,Default,,0,0,0,,And when our finger is lifted
Dialogue: 0,0:04:58.77,0:04:59.78,Default,,0,0,0,,off we're just going to call
Dialogue: 0,0:04:59.78,0:05:00.67,Default,,0,0,0,,continueAnimation.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:02.54,0:05:04.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Now that's really easy, but
Dialogue: 0,0:05:04.06,0:05:05.33,Default,,0,0,0,,there's actually two really
Dialogue: 0,0:05:05.33,0:05:06.63,Default,,0,0,0,,interesting moments that occur
Dialogue: 0,0:05:06.69,0:05:08.22,Default,,0,0,0,,here and that is when we pause
Dialogue: 0,0:05:08.22,0:05:09.27,Default,,0,0,0,,our animation and then when we
Dialogue: 0,0:05:09.31,0:05:10.35,Default,,0,0,0,,continue it, so let's take a
Dialogue: 0,0:05:10.35,0:05:10.93,Default,,0,0,0,,look at those.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:12.35,0:05:13.23,Default,,0,0,0,,So, we've just created our
Dialogue: 0,0:05:13.23,0:05:14.97,Default,,0,0,0,,animator and we're about to
Dialogue: 0,0:05:14.97,0:05:16.31,Default,,0,0,0,,pause it so we can interact with
Dialogue: 0,0:05:16.31,0:05:16.38,Default,,0,0,0,,it.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:16.65,0:05:18.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Notice that our animator has
Dialogue: 0,0:05:18.70,0:05:20.25,Default,,0,0,0,,been created with an ease out
Dialogue: 0,0:05:20.25,0:05:20.87,Default,,0,0,0,,timing function.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:21.34,0:05:22.42,Default,,0,0,0,,So, let's call pause and see
Dialogue: 0,0:05:22.42,0:05:23.57,Default,,0,0,0,,what happens.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:25.40,0:05:27.54,Default,,0,0,0,,So, our animator becomes active,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:28.02,0:05:29.35,Default,,0,0,0,,but we've just converted our
Dialogue: 0,0:05:29.35,0:05:31.27,Default,,0,0,0,,timing curve automatically into
Dialogue: 0,0:05:31.27,0:05:32.19,Default,,0,0,0,,a linear timing curve.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.82,0:05:33.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Why did the property animator do
Dialogue: 0,0:05:33.97,0:05:34.22,Default,,0,0,0,,that?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:35.21,0:05:36.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Well it turns out this makes
Dialogue: 0,0:05:36.60,0:05:38.03,Default,,0,0,0,,scrubbing your animation really
Dialogue: 0,0:05:38.03,0:05:40.01,Default,,0,0,0,,easy because of that property of
Dialogue: 0,0:05:40.01,0:05:41.41,Default,,0,0,0,,linear timing functions where
Dialogue: 0,0:05:41.57,0:05:42.85,Default,,0,0,0,,the fraction of time is equal to
Dialogue: 0,0:05:42.85,0:05:44.41,Default,,0,0,0,,the fraction of progress, you
Dialogue: 0,0:05:44.41,0:05:45.79,Default,,0,0,0,,can now scrub both time and
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.79,0:05:46.97,Default,,0,0,0,,progress uniformly.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:48.93,0:05:49.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Now let's take a look at what
Dialogue: 0,0:05:49.75,0:05:50.95,Default,,0,0,0,,happens when we continue our
Dialogue: 0,0:05:50.95,0:05:51.41,Default,,0,0,0,,animation.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:52.68,0:05:53.28,Default,,0,0,0,,So, we're scrubbing our
Dialogue: 0,0:05:53.28,0:05:55.23,Default,,0,0,0,,animation here and now our
Dialogue: 0,0:05:55.23,0:05:56.36,Default,,0,0,0,,finger is lifted off and we're
Dialogue: 0,0:05:56.36,0:05:58.32,Default,,0,0,0,,about call continueAnimation, so
Dialogue: 0,0:05:58.32,0:06:02.80,Default,,0,0,0,,let's see what that does.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:03.04,0:06:04.44,Default,,0,0,0,,So, we convert back to that ease
Dialogue: 0,0:06:04.44,0:06:06.71,Default,,0,0,0,,out timing function, but also
Dialogue: 0,0:06:06.71,0:06:07.79,Default,,0,0,0,,something interesting happened.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:07.79,0:06:09.59,Default,,0,0,0,,We remapped time in the process.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:10.05,0:06:11.33,Default,,0,0,0,,So, fraction complete which was
Dialogue: 0,0:06:11.33,0:06:14.68,Default,,0,0,0,,once 50% is now 10% and the
Dialogue: 0,0:06:14.68,0:06:16.63,Default,,0,0,0,,reason for that is we want to
Dialogue: 0,0:06:16.63,0:06:18.46,Default,,0,0,0,,keep our progress value stable
Dialogue: 0,0:06:18.46,0:06:19.69,Default,,0,0,0,,when we convert back to that
Dialogue: 0,0:06:19.69,0:06:20.70,Default,,0,0,0,,ease out timing function.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:22.83,0:06:23.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Also, I want to draw attention
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.92,0:06:25.21,Default,,0,0,0,,to our duration factor here,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:25.21,0:06:26.75,Default,,0,0,0,,which is zero and what this
Dialogue: 0,0:06:26.75,0:06:27.87,Default,,0,0,0,,means is for our property
Dialogue: 0,0:06:27.87,0:06:28.80,Default,,0,0,0,,animator to use whatever
Dialogue: 0,0:06:28.80,0:06:30.19,Default,,0,0,0,,remaining time it has left,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:30.69,0:06:32.56,Default,,0,0,0,,which in this case would be 90%
Dialogue: 0,0:06:32.99,0:06:34.31,Default,,0,0,0,,of its original duration.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:34.71,0:06:36.62,Default,,0,0,0,,So, if for example, our animator
Dialogue: 0,0:06:36.62,0:06:37.80,Default,,0,0,0,,was created with a duration of
Dialogue: 0,0:06:37.80,0:06:39.74,Default,,0,0,0,,two seconds it would continue in
Dialogue: 0,0:06:39.74,0:06:40.71,Default,,0,0,0,,1.8 seconds.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:42.65,0:06:44.31,Default,,0,0,0,,So that's how interactive
Dialogue: 0,0:06:44.31,0:06:45.08,Default,,0,0,0,,animations work.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:45.08,0:06:46.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Now let's talk about how to make
Dialogue: 0,0:06:46.37,0:06:47.37,Default,,0,0,0,,our animations fully
Dialogue: 0,0:06:47.37,0:06:47.90,Default,,0,0,0,,interruptible.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:50.01,0:06:51.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Now an interruptible animation
Dialogue: 0,0:06:51.21,0:06:52.19,Default,,0,0,0,,is one in which the user's
Dialogue: 0,0:06:52.19,0:06:53.67,Default,,0,0,0,,actions interrupt or pause a
Dialogue: 0,0:06:53.67,0:06:54.78,Default,,0,0,0,,currently running animation.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:55.50,0:06:56.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Here's an example that you're
Dialogue: 0,0:06:56.34,0:06:57.27,Default,,0,0,0,,probably familiar with, with
Dialogue: 0,0:06:57.27,0:06:57.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Safari.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:57.97,0:06:59.31,Default,,0,0,0,,When you flick your finger, it
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.31,0:07:00.97,Default,,0,0,0,,accelerates and then it sort of
Dialogue: 0,0:07:00.97,0:07:01.70,Default,,0,0,0,,decelerates.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:02.19,0:07:03.12,Default,,0,0,0,,But if you touch the screen
Dialogue: 0,0:07:03.12,0:07:04.29,Default,,0,0,0,,again you interrupt that
Dialogue: 0,0:07:04.29,0:07:05.94,Default,,0,0,0,,animation at which point you can
Dialogue: 0,0:07:05.94,0:07:07.05,Default,,0,0,0,,scrub it.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:08.46,0:07:09.48,Default,,0,0,0,,So, we're going to do one more
Dialogue: 0,0:07:09.48,0:07:11.38,Default,,0,0,0,,demonstration this time and
Dialogue: 0,0:07:11.38,0:07:12.25,Default,,0,0,0,,we're going to add our
Dialogue: 0,0:07:12.25,0:07:13.51,Default,,0,0,0,,PanGestureRecognizer to our
Dialogue: 0,0:07:13.51,0:07:14.91,Default,,0,0,0,,circle, but this time we're
Dialogue: 0,0:07:14.91,0:07:15.92,Default,,0,0,0,,going to let it animate for a
Dialogue: 0,0:07:15.92,0:07:16.77,Default,,0,0,0,,little bit and then we're going
Dialogue: 0,0:07:16.80,0:07:17.77,Default,,0,0,0,,to catch it midflight.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:19.27,0:07:21.00,Default,,0,0,0,,So here it is animating then we
Dialogue: 0,0:07:21.00,0:07:22.80,Default,,0,0,0,,catch it with our finger at this
Dialogue: 0,0:07:22.91,0:07:24.05,Default,,0,0,0,,point we can scrub it, but we've
Dialogue: 0,0:07:24.05,0:07:25.61,Default,,0,0,0,,already seen how that works so
Dialogue: 0,0:07:25.61,0:07:26.25,Default,,0,0,0,,instead, we're just going to
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.25,0:07:27.43,Default,,0,0,0,,lift our finger and continue the
Dialogue: 0,0:07:27.43,0:07:28.49,Default,,0,0,0,,animation to its target
Dialogue: 0,0:07:28.49,0:07:29.00,Default,,0,0,0,,destination.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:33.34,0:07:34.69,Default,,0,0,0,,So, here's the code from before
Dialogue: 0,0:07:34.69,0:07:35.42,Default,,0,0,0,,and we're just going to make a
Dialogue: 0,0:07:35.42,0:07:37.09,Default,,0,0,0,,few changes so we can support
Dialogue: 0,0:07:37.09,0:07:38.25,Default,,0,0,0,,both interactive and
Dialogue: 0,0:07:38.25,0:07:39.38,Default,,0,0,0,,interruptible animations.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:39.38,0:07:41.44,Default,,0,0,0,,So, we're going to introduce a
Dialogue: 0,0:07:41.44,0:07:42.41,Default,,0,0,0,,new method here called
Dialogue: 0,0:07:42.41,0:07:43.94,Default,,0,0,0,,animateTransitionIfNeeded and
Dialogue: 0,0:07:43.94,0:07:46.66,Default,,0,0,0,,this is a custom method, this is
Dialogue: 0,0:07:46.66,0:07:48.23,Default,,0,0,0,,not a UIKit method for example.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:49.05,0:07:50.36,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what this does is it'll
Dialogue: 0,0:07:50.36,0:07:51.61,Default,,0,0,0,,initiate our transition if it
Dialogue: 0,0:07:51.61,0:07:52.55,Default,,0,0,0,,isn't already running.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:53.44,0:07:54.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Were also going to introduce a
Dialogue: 0,0:07:54.32,0:07:55.46,Default,,0,0,0,,new property called
Dialogue: 0,0:07:55.56,0:07:56.73,Default,,0,0,0,,progressWhenInterrupted and this
Dialogue: 0,0:07:57.00,0:07:58.31,Default,,0,0,0,,is going to save any relative
Dialogue: 0,0:07:58.34,0:07:59.62,Default,,0,0,0,,progress made by your animator
Dialogue: 0,0:07:59.62,0:08:00.89,Default,,0,0,0,,prior to it being interrupted.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:00.89,0:08:03.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Now when our gesture begins
Dialogue: 0,0:08:03.54,0:08:04.19,Default,,0,0,0,,we're going to create that
Dialogue: 0,0:08:04.19,0:08:05.43,Default,,0,0,0,,animator again, but this time
Dialogue: 0,0:08:05.43,0:08:06.85,Default,,0,0,0,,only if our transition isn't
Dialogue: 0,0:08:06.85,0:08:07.13,Default,,0,0,0,,running.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:07.74,0:08:08.73,Default,,0,0,0,,We're then going to pause it so
Dialogue: 0,0:08:08.73,0:08:09.71,Default,,0,0,0,,that we can interact with it and
Dialogue: 0,0:08:10.21,0:08:11.31,Default,,0,0,0,,we're going to save any relative
Dialogue: 0,0:08:11.31,0:08:12.77,Default,,0,0,0,,progress made by it prior to
Dialogue: 0,0:08:12.77,0:08:13.53,Default,,0,0,0,,being interrupted.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:15.32,0:08:16.32,Default,,0,0,0,,When our finger moves we're
Dialogue: 0,0:08:16.32,0:08:17.45,Default,,0,0,0,,going to scrub our animator's
Dialogue: 0,0:08:17.45,0:08:19.18,Default,,0,0,0,,fraction complete, but this time
Dialogue: 0,0:08:19.44,0:08:20.10,Default,,0,0,0,,we're going to scrub our
Dialogue: 0,0:08:20.10,0:08:21.60,Default,,0,0,0,,animator based on the distance
Dialogue: 0,0:08:21.60,0:08:23.16,Default,,0,0,0,,our finger has traveled relative
Dialogue: 0,0:08:23.16,0:08:25.21,Default,,0,0,0,,to any progress it made prior to
Dialogue: 0,0:08:25.21,0:08:25.86,Default,,0,0,0,,being interrupted.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:27.64,0:08:28.67,Default,,0,0,0,,And when our finger lifts we're
Dialogue: 0,0:08:28.67,0:08:29.69,Default,,0,0,0,,going to continue our animation.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:30.96,0:08:31.98,Default,,0,0,0,,But to make this example a
Dialogue: 0,0:08:31.98,0:08:33.00,Default,,0,0,0,,little bit more interesting
Dialogue: 0,0:08:33.41,0:08:34.77,Default,,0,0,0,,let's continue with an ease out
Dialogue: 0,0:08:34.77,0:08:36.25,Default,,0,0,0,,timing function and let's assume
Dialogue: 0,0:08:36.25,0:08:37.36,Default,,0,0,0,,that our animation was created
Dialogue: 0,0:08:37.36,0:08:38.46,Default,,0,0,0,,with an ease and timing function
Dialogue: 0,0:08:38.79,0:08:39.90,Default,,0,0,0,,just to see what that does.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:42.81,0:08:44.46,Default,,0,0,0,,So, here we are about to
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.46,0:08:45.88,Default,,0,0,0,,interrupt our animation and
Dialogue: 0,0:08:45.88,0:08:47.43,Default,,0,0,0,,fraction completes about 50% sol
Dialogue: 0,0:08:47.43,0:08:48.72,Default,,0,0,0,,it's ran for about half its
Dialogue: 0,0:08:48.72,0:08:50.29,Default,,0,0,0,,duration and progress is only
Dialogue: 0,0:08:50.29,0:08:51.63,Default,,0,0,0,,about 10% because we're on an
Dialogue: 0,0:08:51.68,0:08:52.69,Default,,0,0,0,,ease out timing function.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:53.15,0:08:54.53,Default,,0,0,0,,So, let's call pause and watch
Dialogue: 0,0:08:55.09,0:08:56.05,Default,,0,0,0,,what happens.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:56.26,0:08:57.68,Default,,0,0,0,,So again, we convert into that
Dialogue: 0,0:08:57.68,0:08:58.67,Default,,0,0,0,,linear timing function to make
Dialogue: 0,0:08:58.67,0:09:00.53,Default,,0,0,0,,scrubbing really easy, but we
Dialogue: 0,0:09:00.53,0:09:02.32,Default,,0,0,0,,also have remapped time just as
Dialogue: 0,0:09:02.32,0:09:03.54,Default,,0,0,0,,we did before to keep progress
Dialogue: 0,0:09:03.54,0:09:04.77,Default,,0,0,0,,stable so our animation doesn't
Dialogue: 0,0:09:04.77,0:09:05.03,Default,,0,0,0,,jump.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:05.89,0:09:06.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Now when we call
Dialogue: 0,0:09:06.57,0:09:08.58,Default,,0,0,0,,continueAnimation we're going to
Dialogue: 0,0:09:08.58,0:09:10.20,Default,,0,0,0,,do so with an ease out timing
Dialogue: 0,0:09:10.20,0:09:11.70,Default,,0,0,0,,function and again, you can see
Dialogue: 0,0:09:12.12,0:09:13.95,Default,,0,0,0,,we convert back into that new
Dialogue: 0,0:09:13.95,0:09:15.62,Default,,0,0,0,,timing function and remap time
Dialogue: 0,0:09:15.62,0:09:15.88,Default,,0,0,0,,again.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:17.13,0:09:18.60,Default,,0,0,0,,So, this is a really subtle
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.60,0:09:20.16,Default,,0,0,0,,aspect of property animators
Dialogue: 0,0:09:20.19,0:09:20.92,Default,,0,0,0,,that's really important to
Dialogue: 0,0:09:20.92,0:09:21.71,Default,,0,0,0,,understand when you're
Dialogue: 0,0:09:21.71,0:09:22.57,Default,,0,0,0,,manipulating them.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:23.19,0:09:27.29,Default,,0,0,0,,So that's how to make animations
Dialogue: 0,0:09:27.29,0:09:28.05,Default,,0,0,0,,fully interactive and
Dialogue: 0,0:09:28.05,0:09:28.60,Default,,0,0,0,,interruptible.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:28.65,0:09:29.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Now let's talk about some of the
Dialogue: 0,0:09:29.68,0:09:30.83,Default,,0,0,0,,new API that we're providing
Dialogue: 0,0:09:30.83,0:09:31.13,Default,,0,0,0,,this year.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:32.69,0:09:35.04,Default,,0,0,0,,So, new in iOS 11 property
Dialogue: 0,0:09:35.04,0:09:36.70,Default,,0,0,0,,animator is getting two new
Dialogue: 0,0:09:36.70,0:09:39.54,Default,,0,0,0,,properties, scrubsLinearly and
Dialogue: 0,0:09:39.54,0:09:40.52,Default,,0,0,0,,pausesOnCompletion.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:41.40,0:09:43.36,Default,,0,0,0,,It's also getting a new behavior
Dialogue: 0,0:09:43.36,0:09:45.72,Default,,0,0,0,,which is starting as paused, so
Dialogue: 0,0:09:45.72,0:09:46.63,Default,,0,0,0,,let's talk about these.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:48.00,0:09:48.82,Default,,0,0,0,,So, in the last couple of
Dialogue: 0,0:09:48.82,0:09:50.44,Default,,0,0,0,,examples you saw that when we
Dialogue: 0,0:09:50.44,0:09:51.84,Default,,0,0,0,,paused our animator it converts
Dialogue: 0,0:09:51.84,0:09:52.90,Default,,0,0,0,,the timing function into a
Dialogue: 0,0:09:52.90,0:09:54.39,Default,,0,0,0,,linear timing function and it
Dialogue: 0,0:09:54.39,0:09:56.14,Default,,0,0,0,,does this to make scrubbing the
Dialogue: 0,0:09:56.28,0:09:57.50,Default,,0,0,0,,progress of your animator really
Dialogue: 0,0:09:57.55,0:09:57.90,Default,,0,0,0,,easy.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:58.70,0:09:59.93,Default,,0,0,0,,But you know sometimes it's
Dialogue: 0,0:09:59.93,0:10:01.06,Default,,0,0,0,,really useful for your animator
Dialogue: 0,0:10:01.06,0:10:02.33,Default,,0,0,0,,to maintain its pacing when it's
Dialogue: 0,0:10:02.33,0:10:03.44,Default,,0,0,0,,being driven interactively.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:04.17,0:10:05.22,Default,,0,0,0,,And now you can do that by
Dialogue: 0,0:10:05.22,0:10:06.52,Default,,0,0,0,,disabling linear scrubbing.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:07.42,0:10:08.56,Default,,0,0,0,,And here's just a quick example
Dialogue: 0,0:10:08.63,0:10:10.51,Default,,0,0,0,,where linearly scrubbing the
Dialogue: 0,0:10:10.51,0:10:12.88,Default,,0,0,0,,opacity of the circle on top and
Dialogue: 0,0:10:12.88,0:10:14.22,Default,,0,0,0,,we're nonlinearly scrubbing the
Dialogue: 0,0:10:14.22,0:10:15.56,Default,,0,0,0,,opacity of the circle on the
Dialogue: 0,0:10:15.56,0:10:17.00,Default,,0,0,0,,bottom according to an ease out
Dialogue: 0,0:10:17.00,0:10:17.60,Default,,0,0,0,,timing function.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:19.09,0:10:20.23,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll see a little bit later
Dialogue: 0,0:10:20.23,0:10:21.04,Default,,0,0,0,,when we're coordinating
Dialogue: 0,0:10:21.04,0:10:22.14,Default,,0,0,0,,transitions this could be a
Dialogue: 0,0:10:22.14,0:10:23.46,Default,,0,0,0,,really interesting thing to do
Dialogue: 0,0:10:23.46,0:10:26.43,Default,,0,0,0,,to create some pretty compelling
Dialogue: 0,0:10:26.43,0:10:27.01,Default,,0,0,0,,animations.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:28.91,0:10:30.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Animators can now also pause on
Dialogue: 0,0:10:30.34,0:10:30.83,Default,,0,0,0,,completion.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:32.32,0:10:33.97,Default,,0,0,0,,So, when an animator's
Dialogue: 0,0:10:33.97,0:10:35.32,Default,,0,0,0,,animations finish it will
Dialogue: 0,0:10:35.32,0:10:36.56,Default,,0,0,0,,automatically transition into
Dialogue: 0,0:10:36.56,0:10:37.46,Default,,0,0,0,,the inactive state.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:38.07,0:10:39.30,Default,,0,0,0,,And when it does that it's going
Dialogue: 0,0:10:39.30,0:10:40.59,Default,,0,0,0,,to release any animations that
Dialogue: 0,0:10:40.59,0:10:42.34,Default,,0,0,0,,it was previously tracking which
Dialogue: 0,0:10:42.34,0:10:44.25,Default,,0,0,0,,means you cannot manipulate or
Dialogue: 0,0:10:44.25,0:10:45.52,Default,,0,0,0,,even reverse them after they've
Dialogue: 0,0:10:45.58,0:10:45.97,Default,,0,0,0,,finished.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:46.92,0:10:48.17,Default,,0,0,0,,But now if you set pauses on
Dialogue: 0,0:10:48.17,0:10:50.02,Default,,0,0,0,,completion to true your animator
Dialogue: 0,0:10:50.02,0:10:51.61,Default,,0,0,0,,will pause at 100% fraction
Dialogue: 0,0:10:51.61,0:10:53.32,Default,,0,0,0,,complete allowing you to at any
Dialogue: 0,0:10:53.32,0:10:54.65,Default,,0,0,0,,point in the future reverse
Dialogue: 0,0:10:54.65,0:10:55.29,Default,,0,0,0,,those animations.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:55.92,0:10:58.77,Default,,0,0,0,,And to give you guys a little
Dialogue: 0,0:10:58.77,0:11:00.18,Default,,0,0,0,,bit of insight here we actually
Dialogue: 0,0:11:00.18,0:11:01.29,Default,,0,0,0,,use this in UIKit for
Dialogue: 0,0:11:01.29,0:11:01.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Drag-and-Drop.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:02.73,0:11:04.56,Default,,0,0,0,,So, here's an example of a lift
Dialogue: 0,0:11:04.56,0:11:05.88,Default,,0,0,0,,animation and as you may be
Dialogue: 0,0:11:05.88,0:11:07.21,Default,,0,0,0,,aware, you can provide your own
Dialogue: 0,0:11:07.51,0:11:08.85,Default,,0,0,0,,alongside animations to
Dialogue: 0,0:11:08.85,0:11:09.78,Default,,0,0,0,,customize this.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:10.71,0:11:11.73,Default,,0,0,0,,And we're actually going to
Dialogue: 0,0:11:11.73,0:11:13.66,Default,,0,0,0,,drive those animations by a
Dialogue: 0,0:11:13.66,0:11:15.09,Default,,0,0,0,,property animator that pauses on
Dialogue: 0,0:11:15.09,0:11:16.81,Default,,0,0,0,,completion internally in UIKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:17.69,0:11:18.82,Default,,0,0,0,,And because of that we could
Dialogue: 0,0:11:18.98,0:11:20.88,Default,,0,0,0,,easily reverse those animations
Dialogue: 0,0:11:20.88,0:11:22.67,Default,,0,0,0,,for you at any time after the
Dialogue: 0,0:11:22.83,0:11:25.29,Default,,0,0,0,,user lifts their finger even if
Dialogue: 0,0:11:25.33,0:11:26.52,Default,,0,0,0,,your animations have already
Dialogue: 0,0:11:26.52,0:11:27.00,Default,,0,0,0,,finished.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:30.92,0:11:32.76,Default,,0,0,0,,I also should mention that we're
Dialogue: 0,0:11:32.76,0:11:33.45,Default,,0,0,0,,not going to call your
Dialogue: 0,0:11:33.45,0:11:34.64,Default,,0,0,0,,animator's completion handler
Dialogue: 0,0:11:34.64,0:11:35.90,Default,,0,0,0,,when it pauses on completion,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:36.36,0:11:37.35,Default,,0,0,0,,but if you are interested to
Dialogue: 0,0:11:37.35,0:11:38.29,Default,,0,0,0,,know when those animations have
Dialogue: 0,0:11:38.37,0:11:39.84,Default,,0,0,0,,finished you can simply observe
Dialogue: 0,0:11:39.87,0:11:40.72,Default,,0,0,0,,the running property.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:41.27,0:11:44.91,Default,,0,0,0,,And finally, now you can create
Dialogue: 0,0:11:44.91,0:11:46.43,Default,,0,0,0,,a property animator and start it
Dialogue: 0,0:11:46.43,0:11:47.65,Default,,0,0,0,,before you've provided any
Dialogue: 0,0:11:47.65,0:11:48.50,Default,,0,0,0,,animations to it.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:49.20,0:11:50.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Now what this does is any
Dialogue: 0,0:11:50.65,0:11:51.52,Default,,0,0,0,,animation blocks that you
Dialogue: 0,0:11:51.52,0:11:53.13,Default,,0,0,0,,subsequently provide will be ran
Dialogue: 0,0:11:53.13,0:11:54.78,Default,,0,0,0,,immediately instead of escaping.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:54.78,0:11:56.11,Default,,0,0,0,,And this is great if you're
Dialogue: 0,0:11:56.11,0:11:57.48,Default,,0,0,0,,transitioning any of your UIView
Dialogue: 0,0:11:57.51,0:11:59.09,Default,,0,0,0,,animate code over to using
Dialogue: 0,0:11:59.09,0:11:59.91,Default,,0,0,0,,property animators.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:00.53,0:12:04.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Now I just want to spend a
Dialogue: 0,0:12:04.37,0:12:05.60,Default,,0,0,0,,couple minutes here talking
Dialogue: 0,0:12:05.60,0:12:06.34,Default,,0,0,0,,about springs.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:07.01,0:12:07.87,Default,,0,0,0,,So, spring animations are
Dialogue: 0,0:12:07.87,0:12:10.38,Default,,0,0,0,,pervasive in UIKit in iOS and
Dialogue: 0,0:12:10.38,0:12:11.62,Default,,0,0,0,,they add a sense of realism to
Dialogue: 0,0:12:11.62,0:12:12.31,Default,,0,0,0,,your animations.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:13.55,0:12:14.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Now in UIKit we provide two
Dialogue: 0,0:12:14.86,0:12:16.52,Default,,0,0,0,,kinds of springs, critically
Dialogue: 0,0:12:16.52,0:12:17.94,Default,,0,0,0,,damped springs and under damped
Dialogue: 0,0:12:17.94,0:12:18.23,Default,,0,0,0,,springs.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:19.52,0:12:20.73,Default,,0,0,0,,A critically damped spring is
Dialogue: 0,0:12:20.73,0:12:22.03,Default,,0,0,0,,one which accelerates quickly
Dialogue: 0,0:12:22.03,0:12:23.33,Default,,0,0,0,,and it sort of decelerates just
Dialogue: 0,0:12:23.33,0:12:24.51,Default,,0,0,0,,as quickly hovering over its
Dialogue: 0,0:12:24.51,0:12:27.38,Default,,0,0,0,,target value, whereas an under
Dialogue: 0,0:12:27.38,0:12:28.38,Default,,0,0,0,,damped spring accelerates
Dialogue: 0,0:12:28.38,0:12:30.08,Default,,0,0,0,,quickly beyond its target value
Dialogue: 0,0:12:30.08,0:12:31.05,Default,,0,0,0,,and then oscillates.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:32.83,0:12:34.01,Default,,0,0,0,,So, spring animations are unique
Dialogue: 0,0:12:34.01,0:12:35.65,Default,,0,0,0,,in this way and we think of
Dialogue: 0,0:12:35.65,0:12:36.99,Default,,0,0,0,,spring animations just as we
Dialogue: 0,0:12:36.99,0:12:38.40,Default,,0,0,0,,think about timing curves.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:39.06,0:12:40.29,Default,,0,0,0,,But spring animations are also
Dialogue: 0,0:12:40.29,0:12:41.63,Default,,0,0,0,,unique in that they always
Dialogue: 0,0:12:41.70,0:12:42.74,Default,,0,0,0,,animate from their current
Dialogue: 0,0:12:42.74,0:12:43.58,Default,,0,0,0,,presentation value.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:43.58,0:12:45.14,Default,,0,0,0,,And there are a couple reasons
Dialogue: 0,0:12:45.14,0:12:46.08,Default,,0,0,0,,why we do this.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:47.98,0:12:49.38,Default,,0,0,0,,So, the first is, it may
Dialogue: 0,0:12:49.38,0:12:51.10,Default,,0,0,0,,actually be undefined to convert
Dialogue: 0,0:12:51.10,0:12:52.61,Default,,0,0,0,,a spring animation to a cubic
Dialogue: 0,0:12:52.61,0:12:54.06,Default,,0,0,0,,animation and this is because
Dialogue: 0,0:12:54.06,0:12:55.46,Default,,0,0,0,,cubic timing functions don't
Dialogue: 0,0:12:55.46,0:12:56.47,Default,,0,0,0,,oscillate or overshoot their
Dialogue: 0,0:12:56.47,0:12:58.08,Default,,0,0,0,,value as they're bounded by
Dialogue: 0,0:12:58.08,0:12:59.38,Default,,0,0,0,,minimum and maximum values.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:59.91,0:13:03.53,Default,,0,0,0,,And the second reason it's a
Dialogue: 0,0:13:03.53,0:13:05.02,Default,,0,0,0,,little bit more interesting and
Dialogue: 0,0:13:05.46,0:13:07.63,Default,,0,0,0,,this is if you animate with a
Dialogue: 0,0:13:07.63,0:13:09.14,Default,,0,0,0,,two-dimensional initial velocity
Dialogue: 0,0:13:09.14,0:13:11.20,Default,,0,0,0,,with unique DX and DY components
Dialogue: 0,0:13:11.63,0:13:12.98,Default,,0,0,0,,property animator is actually
Dialogue: 0,0:13:12.98,0:13:14.28,Default,,0,0,0,,going to decompose that for you
Dialogue: 0,0:13:14.61,0:13:15.63,Default,,0,0,0,,and create two spring
Dialogue: 0,0:13:15.63,0:13:16.17,Default,,0,0,0,,animations.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:17.04,0:13:17.95,Default,,0,0,0,,And because those two spring
Dialogue: 0,0:13:17.95,0:13:19.47,Default,,0,0,0,,animations have different
Dialogue: 0,0:13:19.47,0:13:20.66,Default,,0,0,0,,velocities they're going to be
Dialogue: 0,0:13:20.66,0:13:21.64,Default,,0,0,0,,desynchronized so we're not
Dialogue: 0,0:13:21.64,0:13:22.36,Default,,0,0,0,,going to be able to convert
Dialogue: 0,0:13:22.39,0:13:23.97,Default,,0,0,0,,those onto a cubic animation.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:24.55,0:13:28.20,Default,,0,0,0,,So, if you do have to interrupt
Dialogue: 0,0:13:28.20,0:13:29.36,Default,,0,0,0,,the spring animation here are a
Dialogue: 0,0:13:29.36,0:13:30.51,Default,,0,0,0,,few best practices.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:31.64,0:13:32.60,Default,,0,0,0,,So, the first thing you can do
Dialogue: 0,0:13:32.73,0:13:33.84,Default,,0,0,0,,is consider stopping your spring
Dialogue: 0,0:13:33.84,0:13:35.05,Default,,0,0,0,,animation, promoting current
Dialogue: 0,0:13:35.05,0:13:36.17,Default,,0,0,0,,presentation value to model
Dialogue: 0,0:13:36.17,0:13:37.40,Default,,0,0,0,,value, and then creating a
Dialogue: 0,0:13:37.40,0:13:38.47,Default,,0,0,0,,brand-new animation from there.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:39.06,0:13:42.20,Default,,0,0,0,,The second thing you can do is
Dialogue: 0,0:13:42.23,0:13:43.26,Default,,0,0,0,,consider using a critically
Dialogue: 0,0:13:43.26,0:13:44.35,Default,,0,0,0,,damped spring without initial
Dialogue: 0,0:13:44.35,0:13:45.45,Default,,0,0,0,,velocity as these don't
Dialogue: 0,0:13:45.45,0:13:47.03,Default,,0,0,0,,overshoot or oscillate.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:48.42,0:13:50.11,Default,,0,0,0,,And then finally, if you are
Dialogue: 0,0:13:50.11,0:13:51.53,Default,,0,0,0,,animating with a two-dimensional
Dialogue: 0,0:13:51.53,0:13:52.99,Default,,0,0,0,,initial velocity with unique X
Dialogue: 0,0:13:52.99,0:13:54.99,Default,,0,0,0,,and Y components you can
Dialogue: 0,0:13:54.99,0:13:56.26,Default,,0,0,0,,consider decomposing that
Dialogue: 0,0:13:56.26,0:13:58.36,Default,,0,0,0,,yourself and driving the X
Dialogue: 0,0:13:58.36,0:14:00.11,Default,,0,0,0,,animations with one animator and
Dialogue: 0,0:14:00.11,0:14:01.54,Default,,0,0,0,,the Y animations with another.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:03.25,0:14:06.16,Default,,0,0,0,,So that's how property
Dialogue: 0,0:14:06.16,0:14:06.88,Default,,0,0,0,,animations work.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:07.69,0:14:09.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Now let's talk about how to use
Dialogue: 0,0:14:09.12,0:14:10.69,Default,,0,0,0,,all that knowledge to coordinate
Dialogue: 0,0:14:10.80,0:14:11.34,Default,,0,0,0,,animations.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:12.42,0:14:13.73,Default,,0,0,0,,So, for this we're going to
Dialogue: 0,0:14:13.73,0:14:15.09,Default,,0,0,0,,build a fully interactive
Dialogue: 0,0:14:15.09,0:14:16.16,Default,,0,0,0,,interruptible animated
Dialogue: 0,0:14:16.16,0:14:17.79,Default,,0,0,0,,transition that coordinates
Dialogue: 0,0:14:17.79,0:14:19.70,Default,,0,0,0,,across multiple uniquely timed
Dialogue: 0,0:14:19.92,0:14:20.42,Default,,0,0,0,,animators.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:22.38,0:14:23.75,Default,,0,0,0,,So, say that we have an app and
Dialogue: 0,0:14:23.75,0:14:24.78,Default,,0,0,0,,our app is showing some piece of
Dialogue: 0,0:14:24.78,0:14:26.26,Default,,0,0,0,,content and anchored to the
Dialogue: 0,0:14:26.26,0:14:27.32,Default,,0,0,0,,bottom of the screen is the
Dialogue: 0,0:14:27.32,0:14:28.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Comments button and when we tap
Dialogue: 0,0:14:28.92,0:14:30.51,Default,,0,0,0,,on it it expands showing our
Dialogue: 0,0:14:30.51,0:14:31.11,Default,,0,0,0,,comments view.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:32.39,0:14:33.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Now we might implement this
Dialogue: 0,0:14:33.50,0:14:35.39,Default,,0,0,0,,using UIView controller animated
Dialogue: 0,0:14:35.39,0:14:36.67,Default,,0,0,0,,transitioning for example, but
Dialogue: 0,0:14:37.29,0:14:38.92,Default,,0,0,0,,we'd like this to be completely
Dialogue: 0,0:14:38.92,0:14:40.11,Default,,0,0,0,,interactive and interruptible so
Dialogue: 0,0:14:40.11,0:14:41.15,Default,,0,0,0,,I'd like to show you how to do
Dialogue: 0,0:14:41.15,0:14:41.38,Default,,0,0,0,,that.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:41.93,0:14:43.87,Default,,0,0,0,,So, the first thing we're going
Dialogue: 0,0:14:43.87,0:14:45.45,Default,,0,0,0,,to do is add two gesture
Dialogue: 0,0:14:45.45,0:14:46.81,Default,,0,0,0,,recognizers, a tap gesture
Dialogue: 0,0:14:46.81,0:14:48.12,Default,,0,0,0,,recognizer so that we can tap on
Dialogue: 0,0:14:48.12,0:14:49.44,Default,,0,0,0,,it and expands and tap on it
Dialogue: 0,0:14:49.44,0:14:50.54,Default,,0,0,0,,again it will collapse.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:51.02,0:14:52.17,Default,,0,0,0,,We'd also like to be able to tap
Dialogue: 0,0:14:52.17,0:14:53.30,Default,,0,0,0,,on it while that animation is
Dialogue: 0,0:14:53.35,0:14:54.66,Default,,0,0,0,,running so it can be reversed.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:55.67,0:14:56.58,Default,,0,0,0,,And we're going to add a pan
Dialogue: 0,0:14:56.58,0:14:57.53,Default,,0,0,0,,gesture recognizer so we can
Dialogue: 0,0:14:57.57,0:14:58.20,Default,,0,0,0,,interact with it.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:58.99,0:15:00.25,Default,,0,0,0,,So, here's our code form before
Dialogue: 0,0:15:00.92,0:15:01.83,Default,,0,0,0,,and we're going to make just a
Dialogue: 0,0:15:01.83,0:15:03.45,Default,,0,0,0,,couple modifications to it to
Dialogue: 0,0:15:03.45,0:15:04.64,Default,,0,0,0,,create this infrastructure that
Dialogue: 0,0:15:04.64,0:15:05.49,Default,,0,0,0,,we're going to build on.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:06.52,0:15:07.19,Default,,0,0,0,,So, the first thing we're going
Dialogue: 0,0:15:07.19,0:15:08.91,Default,,0,0,0,,to do is we're going to replace
Dialogue: 0,0:15:08.96,0:15:10.06,Default,,0,0,0,,our instance of our property
Dialogue: 0,0:15:10.06,0:15:11.88,Default,,0,0,0,,animator with a collection of
Dialogue: 0,0:15:11.88,0:15:13.16,Default,,0,0,0,,running property animators.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:14.97,0:15:16.75,Default,,0,0,0,,And for that collection of
Dialogue: 0,0:15:16.99,0:15:19.04,Default,,0,0,0,,running property animators if we
Dialogue: 0,0:15:19.04,0:15:20.24,Default,,0,0,0,,ever create a property animator
Dialogue: 0,0:15:20.24,0:15:20.99,Default,,0,0,0,,we're just going to add it to
Dialogue: 0,0:15:21.04,0:15:22.52,Default,,0,0,0,,that collection and let's assume
Dialogue: 0,0:15:22.58,0:15:23.65,Default,,0,0,0,,that when those animations
Dialogue: 0,0:15:23.65,0:15:24.65,Default,,0,0,0,,finish it's automatically
Dialogue: 0,0:15:24.65,0:15:25.00,Default,,0,0,0,,removed.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:26.55,0:15:27.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Next, we're going to reintroduce
Dialogue: 0,0:15:27.88,0:15:29.70,Default,,0,0,0,,our animateTransitionIfNeeded
Dialogue: 0,0:15:29.70,0:15:30.94,Default,,0,0,0,,method and it's going to take a
Dialogue: 0,0:15:30.94,0:15:32.39,Default,,0,0,0,,target state to animate to.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:32.98,0:15:36.03,Default,,0,0,0,,So, if we look at this if our
Dialogue: 0,0:15:36.03,0:15:37.41,Default,,0,0,0,,runningAnimators.isEmpty that
Dialogue: 0,0:15:37.41,0:15:38.36,Default,,0,0,0,,means there's no transition
Dialogue: 0,0:15:38.36,0:15:39.72,Default,,0,0,0,,currently running, so we're
Dialogue: 0,0:15:39.72,0:15:41.04,Default,,0,0,0,,going to initiate a transition
Dialogue: 0,0:15:41.04,0:15:41.96,Default,,0,0,0,,if that is the case.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:41.96,0:15:43.00,Default,,0,0,0,,And we're going to do that by
Dialogue: 0,0:15:43.00,0:15:44.48,Default,,0,0,0,,creating a new property animator
Dialogue: 0,0:15:44.48,0:15:45.56,Default,,0,0,0,,for our frame which is going to
Dialogue: 0,0:15:45.56,0:15:46.72,Default,,0,0,0,,use a critically damped spring.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:46.72,0:15:48.46,Default,,0,0,0,,We're then going to perform our
Dialogue: 0,0:15:48.46,0:15:49.95,Default,,0,0,0,,animations and we're going to
Dialogue: 0,0:15:49.95,0:15:51.45,Default,,0,0,0,,start that animator and add it
Dialogue: 0,0:15:51.45,0:15:52.36,Default,,0,0,0,,to that collection of running
Dialogue: 0,0:15:52.36,0:15:52.80,Default,,0,0,0,,animators.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:57.05,0:15:57.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Next, in our tap gesture
Dialogue: 0,0:15:57.90,0:15:58.96,Default,,0,0,0,,recognizer handler we're going
Dialogue: 0,0:15:58.96,0:16:00.50,Default,,0,0,0,,to call this method and this is
Dialogue: 0,0:16:00.50,0:16:02.37,Default,,0,0,0,,going to animate or reverse our
Dialogue: 0,0:16:02.37,0:16:03.17,Default,,0,0,0,,running transition.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:03.73,0:16:05.42,Default,,0,0,0,,So, if our transition isn't
Dialogue: 0,0:16:05.42,0:16:06.35,Default,,0,0,0,,running we're going to just
Dialogue: 0,0:16:06.41,0:16:07.48,Default,,0,0,0,,initiate our transition,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:08.14,0:16:09.79,Default,,0,0,0,,otherwise we're going to iterate
Dialogue: 0,0:16:09.79,0:16:10.92,Default,,0,0,0,,through all of our running
Dialogue: 0,0:16:10.92,0:16:12.35,Default,,0,0,0,,property animators and reverse
Dialogue: 0,0:16:12.35,0:16:12.53,Default,,0,0,0,,them.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:17.07,0:16:18.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Now for these next three methods
Dialogue: 0,0:16:18.36,0:16:19.49,Default,,0,0,0,,we're just going to extract our
Dialogue: 0,0:16:19.49,0:16:21.16,Default,,0,0,0,,pan gesture recognizer handling
Dialogue: 0,0:16:21.16,0:16:23.14,Default,,0,0,0,,code from before, so I'm just
Dialogue: 0,0:16:23.14,0:16:24.40,Default,,0,0,0,,going to quickly summarize what
Dialogue: 0,0:16:24.40,0:16:24.76,Default,,0,0,0,,these do.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:25.43,0:16:26.02,Default,,0,0,0,,So, for
Dialogue: 0,0:16:26.02,0:16:27.36,Default,,0,0,0,,startInteractiveTransition this
Dialogue: 0,0:16:27.36,0:16:28.54,Default,,0,0,0,,is called when your gesture
Dialogue: 0,0:16:28.54,0:16:29.85,Default,,0,0,0,,begins and it's just going to
Dialogue: 0,0:16:29.85,0:16:30.93,Default,,0,0,0,,initiate the transition if it
Dialogue: 0,0:16:30.93,0:16:32.68,Default,,0,0,0,,isn't running, pause all of your
Dialogue: 0,0:16:32.68,0:16:34.51,Default,,0,0,0,,animators uniformly, and save
Dialogue: 0,0:16:34.51,0:16:36.10,Default,,0,0,0,,any relative progress made by
Dialogue: 0,0:16:36.10,0:16:36.28,Default,,0,0,0,,them.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:38.42,0:16:39.77,Default,,0,0,0,,UpdateInteractiveTransition is
Dialogue: 0,0:16:39.77,0:16:41.56,Default,,0,0,0,,going to scrub your animators
Dialogue: 0,0:16:41.56,0:16:43.94,Default,,0,0,0,,uniformly relative to the
Dialogue: 0,0:16:43.94,0:16:45.37,Default,,0,0,0,,distance your finger travels and
Dialogue: 0,0:16:45.41,0:16:47.23,Default,,0,0,0,,any progress that your animators
Dialogue: 0,0:16:47.23,0:16:48.49,Default,,0,0,0,,made prior to being interrupted.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:49.47,0:16:50.40,Default,,0,0,0,,And then finally, when your
Dialogue: 0,0:16:50.40,0:16:51.29,Default,,0,0,0,,finger is lifted we just call
Dialogue: 0,0:16:51.29,0:16:52.67,Default,,0,0,0,,continue animation on all your
Dialogue: 0,0:16:52.67,0:16:53.88,Default,,0,0,0,,animators conditionally
Dialogue: 0,0:16:53.88,0:16:54.88,Default,,0,0,0,,reversing them based on the
Dialogue: 0,0:16:54.88,0:16:55.74,Default,,0,0,0,,direction your finger was
Dialogue: 0,0:16:55.74,0:16:56.13,Default,,0,0,0,,traveling.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:57.91,0:16:58.72,Default,,0,0,0,,So, let's check this out.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:00.51,0:17:02.13,Default,,0,0,0,,So, we can drive our animation
Dialogue: 0,0:17:02.22,0:17:04.34,Default,,0,0,0,,non-interactively by tapping, we
Dialogue: 0,0:17:04.34,0:17:05.69,Default,,0,0,0,,can also interactively drive it
Dialogue: 0,0:17:06.58,0:17:07.89,Default,,0,0,0,,by pulling up or pulling down,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:09.54,0:17:11.70,Default,,0,0,0,,and we can tap on it again while
Dialogue: 0,0:17:11.70,0:17:12.87,Default,,0,0,0,,it's running to interrupt it and
Dialogue: 0,0:17:12.87,0:17:13.39,Default,,0,0,0,,reverse it.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:14.42,0:17:15.85,Default,,0,0,0,,And we can also capture
Dialogue: 0,0:17:15.85,0:17:17.33,Default,,0,0,0,,animation while it's running and
Dialogue: 0,0:17:17.33,0:17:18.41,Default,,0,0,0,,at which point we can scrub it.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:19.95,0:17:21.27,Default,,0,0,0,,So now we've created this
Dialogue: 0,0:17:21.34,0:17:23.24,Default,,0,0,0,,infrastructure and right now we
Dialogue: 0,0:17:23.24,0:17:24.46,Default,,0,0,0,,just have a frame animation
Dialogue: 0,0:17:24.46,0:17:25.68,Default,,0,0,0,,which isn't that interesting, so
Dialogue: 0,0:17:25.68,0:17:26.54,Default,,0,0,0,,let's make this a little bit
Dialogue: 0,0:17:26.54,0:17:27.10,Default,,0,0,0,,more interesting.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:29.05,0:17:29.94,Default,,0,0,0,,So, first thing we're going to
Dialogue: 0,0:17:29.94,0:17:30.61,Default,,0,0,0,,do is we're going to add an
Dialogue: 0,0:17:30.64,0:17:31.40,Default,,0,0,0,,interactive blur.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:32.60,0:17:35.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Now in iOS 8 we introduced
Dialogue: 0,0:17:35.35,0:17:37.29,Default,,0,0,0,,UIVisualEffectView, which allows
Dialogue: 0,0:17:37.29,0:17:39.06,Default,,0,0,0,,us to add blur and vibrancy to
Dialogue: 0,0:17:39.06,0:17:39.70,Default,,0,0,0,,our view hierarchy.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:39.70,0:17:42.23,Default,,0,0,0,,And it turns out that the
Dialogue: 0,0:17:42.32,0:17:43.04,Default,,0,0,0,,effects property of
Dialogue: 0,0:17:43.04,0:17:43.98,Default,,0,0,0,,VisualEffectsView is an
Dialogue: 0,0:17:44.03,0:17:46.00,Default,,0,0,0,,animatable property so that's
Dialogue: 0,0:17:46.00,0:17:46.24,Default,,0,0,0,,great.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:47.14,0:17:48.20,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what we're going to do here
Dialogue: 0,0:17:48.50,0:17:49.86,Default,,0,0,0,,is the only code changes we're
Dialogue: 0,0:17:49.86,0:17:51.07,Default,,0,0,0,,going to make is to animate
Dialogue: 0,0:17:51.07,0:17:53.10,Default,,0,0,0,,transition if needed and we're
Dialogue: 0,0:17:53.10,0:17:54.15,Default,,0,0,0,,just going to create a new
Dialogue: 0,0:17:54.15,0:17:55.95,Default,,0,0,0,,animator for our blur, which is
Dialogue: 0,0:17:55.95,0:17:57.03,Default,,0,0,0,,going to use a critically damped
Dialogue: 0,0:17:57.03,0:17:57.99,Default,,0,0,0,,spring at least for now.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:58.91,0:17:59.96,Default,,0,0,0,,And then we're going to perform
Dialogue: 0,0:17:59.96,0:18:01.03,Default,,0,0,0,,our animations here either
Dialogue: 0,0:18:01.03,0:18:02.15,Default,,0,0,0,,setting or unsetting the blur
Dialogue: 0,0:18:02.15,0:18:03.74,Default,,0,0,0,,effect, starting our blur
Dialogue: 0,0:18:03.74,0:18:04.90,Default,,0,0,0,,animator and adding it to that
Dialogue: 0,0:18:04.90,0:18:06.67,Default,,0,0,0,,collection and here's what we
Dialogue: 0,0:18:06.67,0:18:06.87,Default,,0,0,0,,get.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:13.24,0:18:14.05,Default,,0,0,0,,So, we can now have an
Dialogue: 0,0:18:14.05,0:18:17.92,Default,,0,0,0,,interactive blur animation, but.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:17.92,0:18:22.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's see that again in slow
Dialogue: 0,0:18:22.34,0:18:24.08,Default,,0,0,0,,motion because I've got to be
Dialogue: 0,0:18:24.08,0:18:25.43,Default,,0,0,0,,honest with you guys, I don't
Dialogue: 0,0:18:25.43,0:18:26.50,Default,,0,0,0,,know if I'm really feeling this
Dialogue: 0,0:18:26.54,0:18:27.47,Default,,0,0,0,,blur animation right now.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:28.53,0:18:29.86,Default,,0,0,0,,I feel like it's animating
Dialogue: 0,0:18:29.86,0:18:30.99,Default,,0,0,0,,potentially a little bit too
Dialogue: 0,0:18:30.99,0:18:31.42,Default,,0,0,0,,quickly.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:32.51,0:18:34.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Now let's drive this and take a
Dialogue: 0,0:18:34.08,0:18:34.56,Default,,0,0,0,,look at it.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:35.33,0:18:36.32,Default,,0,0,0,,So maybe it looks a little
Dialogue: 0,0:18:36.32,0:18:37.49,Default,,0,0,0,,better, but it still doesn't
Dialogue: 0,0:18:37.49,0:18:38.09,Default,,0,0,0,,look quite right.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:38.09,0:18:40.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Now there are a few reasons for
Dialogue: 0,0:18:40.25,0:18:40.42,Default,,0,0,0,,this.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:41.79,0:18:42.99,Default,,0,0,0,,The first is because we're using
Dialogue: 0,0:18:42.99,0:18:44.39,Default,,0,0,0,,a critically damped spring our
Dialogue: 0,0:18:44.39,0:18:45.64,Default,,0,0,0,,blur is going to animate in too
Dialogue: 0,0:18:45.64,0:18:46.05,Default,,0,0,0,,quickly.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:47.22,0:18:48.48,Default,,0,0,0,,And because our property
Dialogue: 0,0:18:48.48,0:18:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,animator is going to linearly
Dialogue: 0,0:18:50.00,0:18:51.51,Default,,0,0,0,,scrub it our blur is still going
Dialogue: 0,0:18:51.51,0:18:52.63,Default,,0,0,0,,to animate in a little bit too
Dialogue: 0,0:18:52.63,0:18:53.76,Default,,0,0,0,,quickly and it's going animate
Dialogue: 0,0:18:53.76,0:18:54.65,Default,,0,0,0,,out too slowly.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:55.73,0:18:57.03,Default,,0,0,0,,So, in order to fix this, we're
Dialogue: 0,0:18:57.14,0:18:58.10,Default,,0,0,0,,actually going to provide our
Dialogue: 0,0:18:58.10,0:18:59.34,Default,,0,0,0,,own custom timing curves.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:59.78,0:19:01.34,Default,,0,0,0,,So, our custom ease in function
Dialogue: 0,0:19:01.34,0:19:02.35,Default,,0,0,0,,so that our blur animates in
Dialogue: 0,0:19:02.44,0:19:04.26,Default,,0,0,0,,really slowly and a custom ease
Dialogue: 0,0:19:04.26,0:19:05.24,Default,,0,0,0,,out timing function so it
Dialogue: 0,0:19:05.24,0:19:06.70,Default,,0,0,0,,animates out really quickly.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:07.48,0:19:08.84,Default,,0,0,0,,And because these are inversions
Dialogue: 0,0:19:08.84,0:19:10.18,Default,,0,0,0,,of each other we're going to get
Dialogue: 0,0:19:10.18,0:19:12.10,Default,,0,0,0,,symmetric pacing, which means
Dialogue: 0,0:19:12.10,0:19:13.45,Default,,0,0,0,,that the path of our animation
Dialogue: 0,0:19:13.45,0:19:14.77,Default,,0,0,0,,on its way out will match that
Dialogue: 0,0:19:14.77,0:19:15.76,Default,,0,0,0,,of its path on the way in.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:17.39,0:19:18.29,Default,,0,0,0,,So, here's the code for this,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:18.46,0:19:19.67,Default,,0,0,0,,we're just creating cubic timing
Dialogue: 0,0:19:19.67,0:19:20.93,Default,,0,0,0,,parameters based on the target
Dialogue: 0,0:19:20.93,0:19:22.97,Default,,0,0,0,,state and we're going to disable
Dialogue: 0,0:19:22.97,0:19:24.26,Default,,0,0,0,,linear scrubbing here so that
Dialogue: 0,0:19:24.26,0:19:25.44,Default,,0,0,0,,our animator maintains its
Dialogue: 0,0:19:25.50,0:19:26.64,Default,,0,0,0,,pacing when we're driving it
Dialogue: 0,0:19:26.64,0:19:27.26,Default,,0,0,0,,interactively.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:28.47,0:19:29.42,Default,,0,0,0,,So, let's check this out again.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:34.06,0:19:34.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Much better.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:34.85,0:19:36.34,Default,,0,0,0,,It's really subtle, but it's
Dialogue: 0,0:19:36.34,0:19:37.29,Default,,0,0,0,,much better this time.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:37.56,0:19:39.22,Default,,0,0,0,,And let's also do that a little
Dialogue: 0,0:19:39.22,0:19:40.31,Default,,0,0,0,,bit more slowly so you can
Dialogue: 0,0:19:40.31,0:19:41.25,Default,,0,0,0,,really get a sense of what it
Dialogue: 0,0:19:41.25,0:19:41.63,Default,,0,0,0,,looks like.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:47.06,0:19:47.97,Default,,0,0,0,,And also, let's drive that
Dialogue: 0,0:19:47.97,0:19:48.86,Default,,0,0,0,,interactively so you can see
Dialogue: 0,0:19:48.86,0:19:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,that it does indeed maintain its
Dialogue: 0,0:19:50.04,0:19:51.21,Default,,0,0,0,,pacing when you're driving it
Dialogue: 0,0:19:51.21,0:19:51.72,Default,,0,0,0,,interactively.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:56.05,0:19:57.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Cool, so now we have two
Dialogue: 0,0:19:58.08,0:19:59.55,Default,,0,0,0,,property animators with unique
Dialogue: 0,0:19:59.55,0:20:00.47,Default,,0,0,0,,timing characteristics
Dialogue: 0,0:20:00.65,0:20:01.63,Default,,0,0,0,,contributing to our overall
Dialogue: 0,0:20:01.63,0:20:02.17,Default,,0,0,0,,transition.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:02.43,0:20:04.01,Default,,0,0,0,,But let's make it a little bit
Dialogue: 0,0:20:04.01,0:20:04.67,Default,,0,0,0,,more interesting.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:05.15,0:20:06.53,Default,,0,0,0,,I'd now like to demonstrate a
Dialogue: 0,0:20:06.53,0:20:07.75,Default,,0,0,0,,technique I like to call view
Dialogue: 0,0:20:07.75,0:20:08.17,Default,,0,0,0,,morphing.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:09.24,0:20:10.93,Default,,0,0,0,,So, say that we have a label; in
Dialogue: 0,0:20:10.93,0:20:12.68,Default,,0,0,0,,this case we have a label.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:12.68,0:20:14.17,Default,,0,0,0,,It's blue, it's kind of small,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:14.53,0:20:16.10,Default,,0,0,0,,it's got a regular typeface and
Dialogue: 0,0:20:16.10,0:20:17.14,Default,,0,0,0,,let's say we want it to be a lot
Dialogue: 0,0:20:17.14,0:20:18.25,Default,,0,0,0,,bigger, maybe a different color,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:18.25,0:20:19.32,Default,,0,0,0,,maybe a heavier typeface.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:19.99,0:20:21.29,Default,,0,0,0,,What would that transition look
Dialogue: 0,0:20:21.81,0:20:21.91,Default,,0,0,0,,like?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:22.56,0:20:24.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Well this is what I call view
Dialogue: 0,0:20:24.74,0:20:26.04,Default,,0,0,0,,morphing, it's the scaling
Dialogue: 0,0:20:26.04,0:20:27.77,Default,,0,0,0,,translation and opacity blending
Dialogue: 0,0:20:27.80,0:20:28.59,Default,,0,0,0,,of two views.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:29.33,0:20:30.36,Default,,0,0,0,,So, in this case, we're going to
Dialogue: 0,0:20:30.36,0:20:32.02,Default,,0,0,0,,use UILabels, but this technique
Dialogue: 0,0:20:32.02,0:20:33.49,Default,,0,0,0,,is generally applicable to any
Dialogue: 0,0:20:33.49,0:20:35.01,Default,,0,0,0,,view or view hierarchy; not just
Dialogue: 0,0:20:35.01,0:20:35.39,Default,,0,0,0,,labels.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:37.12,0:20:38.55,Default,,0,0,0,,So, [inaudible] we're going to
Dialogue: 0,0:20:38.55,0:20:39.50,Default,,0,0,0,,take our comments label and
Dialogue: 0,0:20:39.50,0:20:40.66,Default,,0,0,0,,we're going to make it blue and
Dialogue: 0,0:20:40.66,0:20:41.80,Default,,0,0,0,,when it expands we're going to
Dialogue: 0,0:20:41.80,0:20:42.80,Default,,0,0,0,,want it to look like this.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:43.07,0:20:44.47,Default,,0,0,0,,And notice it's much darker, but
Dialogue: 0,0:20:44.47,0:20:45.95,Default,,0,0,0,,it's also slightly inset from
Dialogue: 0,0:20:45.95,0:20:47.07,Default,,0,0,0,,the top of its parent view.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:48.48,0:20:49.91,Default,,0,0,0,,And the way that we're going to
Dialogue: 0,0:20:49.91,0:20:50.98,Default,,0,0,0,,animate that is like this.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:59.38,0:21:00.41,Default,,0,0,0,,So, how are we going to build
Dialogue: 0,0:21:00.41,0:21:00.50,Default,,0,0,0,,this?
Dialogue: 0,0:21:00.98,0:21:02.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, UILabels don't expose any
Dialogue: 0,0:21:02.32,0:21:03.66,Default,,0,0,0,,animatable properties, but
Dialogue: 0,0:21:03.66,0:21:04.56,Default,,0,0,0,,that's okay because as I
Dialogue: 0,0:21:04.56,0:21:05.55,Default,,0,0,0,,mentioned, this is generally
Dialogue: 0,0:21:05.55,0:21:06.52,Default,,0,0,0,,application to any view or view
Dialogue: 0,0:21:06.52,0:21:07.56,Default,,0,0,0,,hierarchy, not just labels.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:07.73,0:21:10.41,Default,,0,0,0,,What we're going to do is use
Dialogue: 0,0:21:10.41,0:21:11.60,Default,,0,0,0,,UIView's oft overlooked
Dialogue: 0,0:21:11.67,0:21:13.53,Default,,0,0,0,,transform property and we're
Dialogue: 0,0:21:13.53,0:21:14.73,Default,,0,0,0,,going to compute the scale and
Dialogue: 0,0:21:14.73,0:21:16.25,Default,,0,0,0,,translation for both of our
Dialogue: 0,0:21:16.25,0:21:17.91,Default,,0,0,0,,labels so that we can blend them
Dialogue: 0,0:21:17.91,0:21:18.58,Default,,0,0,0,,into each other.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:19.19,0:21:20.77,Default,,0,0,0,,And we're also going to animate
Dialogue: 0,0:21:20.77,0:21:21.97,Default,,0,0,0,,their opacities so that we can
Dialogue: 0,0:21:21.97,0:21:22.87,Default,,0,0,0,,blend them together.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:22.87,0:21:25.54,Default,,0,0,0,,So, first thing we're going to
Dialogue: 0,0:21:25.54,0:21:26.63,Default,,0,0,0,,do is compute the scale.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:27.09,0:21:29.30,Default,,0,0,0,,It turns out this is really easy
Dialogue: 0,0:21:29.30,0:21:30.57,Default,,0,0,0,,to do, it's just a simple
Dialogue: 0,0:21:30.57,0:21:31.94,Default,,0,0,0,,dimensional ratio based on the
Dialogue: 0,0:21:31.94,0:21:32.84,Default,,0,0,0,,target dimension and your
Dialogue: 0,0:21:32.84,0:21:33.55,Default,,0,0,0,,current dimension.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:33.55,0:21:35.46,Default,,0,0,0,,And, in fact, once you computed
Dialogue: 0,0:21:35.46,0:21:36.98,Default,,0,0,0,,one of these you basically get
Dialogue: 0,0:21:36.98,0:21:38.14,Default,,0,0,0,,the other one for free by taking
Dialogue: 0,0:21:38.14,0:21:38.75,Default,,0,0,0,,the inverse.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:38.75,0:21:42.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Now computing translations is a
Dialogue: 0,0:21:42.04,0:21:43.58,Default,,0,0,0,,little bit more interesting and
Dialogue: 0,0:21:43.58,0:21:45.54,Default,,0,0,0,,this is because we're animating
Dialogue: 0,0:21:45.54,0:21:46.56,Default,,0,0,0,,our scale, which is going to
Dialogue: 0,0:21:46.56,0:21:47.64,Default,,0,0,0,,affect our bounds during the
Dialogue: 0,0:21:47.64,0:21:49.46,Default,,0,0,0,,transition, so we can't just
Dialogue: 0,0:21:49.46,0:21:50.80,Default,,0,0,0,,simply take the Y offsets.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:50.80,0:21:54.09,Default,,0,0,0,,What we can do is pre-apply that
Dialogue: 0,0:21:54.09,0:21:55.75,Default,,0,0,0,,scale of transform in order to
Dialogue: 0,0:21:55.75,0:21:57.41,Default,,0,0,0,,obtain a new value for our Y
Dialogue: 0,0:21:57.41,0:21:58.50,Default,,0,0,0,,offsets and we could use that
Dialogue: 0,0:21:58.50,0:21:59.26,Default,,0,0,0,,for our translation.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:00.94,0:22:01.88,Default,,0,0,0,,And now we're going to drive
Dialogue: 0,0:22:01.88,0:22:03.81,Default,,0,0,0,,this using three animators, a
Dialogue: 0,0:22:03.81,0:22:05.30,Default,,0,0,0,,critically damped spring to
Dialogue: 0,0:22:05.30,0:22:06.52,Default,,0,0,0,,drive our transform so that it
Dialogue: 0,0:22:06.52,0:22:08.14,Default,,0,0,0,,follows the overall path of the
Dialogue: 0,0:22:08.14,0:22:10.17,Default,,0,0,0,,transition and then ease in and
Dialogue: 0,0:22:10.17,0:22:11.66,Default,,0,0,0,,ease out animators to perform
Dialogue: 0,0:22:11.66,0:22:13.24,Default,,0,0,0,,the opacity blending, both of
Dialogue: 0,0:22:13.24,0:22:14.42,Default,,0,0,0,,which are going to scrub
Dialogue: 0,0:22:14.42,0:22:15.09,Default,,0,0,0,,nonlinearly.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:15.66,0:22:17.92,Default,,0,0,0,,And here's the code for this and
Dialogue: 0,0:22:17.92,0:22:19.34,Default,,0,0,0,,I've also omitted some of the
Dialogue: 0,0:22:19.34,0:22:20.25,Default,,0,0,0,,repetitive bits.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:20.60,0:22:21.73,Default,,0,0,0,,So, we created transform
Dialogue: 0,0:22:21.73,0:22:22.64,Default,,0,0,0,,animator, we animate the
Dialogue: 0,0:22:22.64,0:22:23.93,Default,,0,0,0,,transform of our labels.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:24.40,0:22:25.68,Default,,0,0,0,,The incoming label is getting
Dialogue: 0,0:22:25.68,0:22:27.40,Default,,0,0,0,,the identity transform and
Dialogue: 0,0:22:27.40,0:22:28.73,Default,,0,0,0,,that's because it's already been
Dialogue: 0,0:22:28.73,0:22:30.35,Default,,0,0,0,,pre-scaled and translated down
Dialogue: 0,0:22:30.63,0:22:32.37,Default,,0,0,0,,to match the bounds of the
Dialogue: 0,0:22:32.43,0:22:33.12,Default,,0,0,0,,outgoing label.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:33.98,0:22:35.12,Default,,0,0,0,,And the outgoing label is going
Dialogue: 0,0:22:35.12,0:22:36.09,Default,,0,0,0,,to get transformed such that it
Dialogue: 0,0:22:36.09,0:22:37.51,Default,,0,0,0,,matches the bounds of the
Dialogue: 0,0:22:37.51,0:22:39.10,Default,,0,0,0,,incoming label prior to it being
Dialogue: 0,0:22:39.10,0:22:39.50,Default,,0,0,0,,animated.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:39.50,0:22:42.09,Default,,0,0,0,,And then we create two property
Dialogue: 0,0:22:42.09,0:22:43.31,Default,,0,0,0,,animators here to blend our
Dialogue: 0,0:22:43.31,0:22:44.62,Default,,0,0,0,,alphas, we disable linear
Dialogue: 0,0:22:44.62,0:22:45.72,Default,,0,0,0,,scrubbing here so they maintain
Dialogue: 0,0:22:45.72,0:22:48.05,Default,,0,0,0,,their pacing and let's see what
Dialogue: 0,0:22:48.05,0:22:50.65,Default,,0,0,0,,that gets us.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:51.26,0:22:53.53,Default,,0,0,0,,So again, non-interactively we
Dialogue: 0,0:22:53.53,0:22:55.94,Default,,0,0,0,,can animate this transition, but
Dialogue: 0,0:22:57.27,0:22:58.69,Default,,0,0,0,,we can also interactively
Dialogue: 0,0:22:58.69,0:23:00.04,Default,,0,0,0,,animate it and it looks great.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:02.67,0:23:04.06,Default,,0,0,0,,And we can even animate it and
Dialogue: 0,0:23:04.06,0:23:05.61,Default,,0,0,0,,then interrupt it and it just
Dialogue: 0,0:23:05.68,0:23:06.13,Default,,0,0,0,,works.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:07.71,0:23:09.98,Default,,0,0,0,,What I think is really cool --
Dialogue: 0,0:23:10.52,0:23:15.61,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:23:16.11,0:23:16.68,Default,,0,0,0,,What I think is really cool
Dialogue: 0,0:23:16.68,0:23:18.44,Default,,0,0,0,,about this is we now have one
Dialogue: 0,0:23:18.44,0:23:20.06,Default,,0,0,0,,cohesive animated transition
Dialogue: 0,0:23:20.06,0:23:21.49,Default,,0,0,0,,that's being driven by six
Dialogue: 0,0:23:21.64,0:23:22.99,Default,,0,0,0,,different property animators,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:23.42,0:23:24.59,Default,,0,0,0,,five of which have their own
Dialogue: 0,0:23:24.77,0:23:25.72,Default,,0,0,0,,timing characteristics.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:26.58,0:23:27.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Now being able to do this prior
Dialogue: 0,0:23:27.93,0:23:29.47,Default,,0,0,0,,to property animators required a
Dialogue: 0,0:23:29.63,0:23:31.52,Default,,0,0,0,,ton of code and complexity, but
Dialogue: 0,0:23:31.52,0:23:32.61,Default,,0,0,0,,now with this infrastructure
Dialogue: 0,0:23:32.61,0:23:34.35,Default,,0,0,0,,we've set up we can use property
Dialogue: 0,0:23:34.35,0:23:35.53,Default,,0,0,0,,animators to easily achieve
Dialogue: 0,0:23:35.53,0:23:37.15,Default,,0,0,0,,these effects just by declaring
Dialogue: 0,0:23:37.15,0:23:38.41,Default,,0,0,0,,our timing characteristics and
Dialogue: 0,0:23:38.41,0:23:39.30,Default,,0,0,0,,scrubbing behaviors.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:41.63,0:23:42.53,Default,,0,0,0,,So that's how to coordinate
Dialogue: 0,0:23:42.53,0:23:43.15,Default,,0,0,0,,animations.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:44.07,0:23:45.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Now let's talk about some tips
Dialogue: 0,0:23:45.23,0:23:46.22,Default,,0,0,0,,and tricks and some additional
Dialogue: 0,0:23:46.22,0:23:47.62,Default,,0,0,0,,techniques that you can use when
Dialogue: 0,0:23:47.62,0:23:48.62,Default,,0,0,0,,you're creating animations for
Dialogue: 0,0:23:48.62,0:23:49.07,Default,,0,0,0,,users.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:51.01,0:23:52.35,Default,,0,0,0,,So, is there anyone out there
Dialogue: 0,0:23:52.35,0:23:53.52,Default,,0,0,0,,that's ever tried to animate a
Dialogue: 0,0:23:53.52,0:23:54.34,Default,,0,0,0,,corner radius before?
Dialogue: 0,0:23:55.36,0:23:56.57,Default,,0,0,0,,I imagine maybe a few of you.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:57.76,0:23:59.36,Default,,0,0,0,,So, to do this you pretty much
Dialogue: 0,0:23:59.36,0:24:00.61,Default,,0,0,0,,have to manually set your corner
Dialogue: 0,0:24:00.61,0:24:01.79,Default,,0,0,0,,radius or if you want to animate
Dialogue: 0,0:24:01.79,0:24:03.36,Default,,0,0,0,,it you have to create a CA basic
Dialogue: 0,0:24:03.36,0:24:04.50,Default,,0,0,0,,animation and set its to and
Dialogue: 0,0:24:04.50,0:24:05.05,Default,,0,0,0,,from values.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:05.45,0:24:08.63,Default,,0,0,0,,What we'd like to do is animate
Dialogue: 0,0:24:08.63,0:24:10.07,Default,,0,0,0,,our corner radius such that it's
Dialogue: 0,0:24:10.07,0:24:10.81,Default,,0,0,0,,interactive.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:12.24,0:24:14.85,Default,,0,0,0,,So, how are we going to do this?
Dialogue: 0,0:24:16.14,0:24:17.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Well I'm really happy to let you
Dialogue: 0,0:24:17.06,0:24:18.51,Default,,0,0,0,,guys know that corner radius is
Dialogue: 0,0:24:18.51,0:24:20.41,Default,,0,0,0,,now a fully animatable property
Dialogue: 0,0:24:20.51,0:24:20.94,Default,,0,0,0,,in UIKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:21.52,0:24:27.57,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:24:28.07,0:24:29.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Now because UIView doesn't
Dialogue: 0,0:24:29.24,0:24:30.36,Default,,0,0,0,,expose the corner radius
Dialogue: 0,0:24:30.41,0:24:31.78,Default,,0,0,0,,property you actually have to
Dialogue: 0,0:24:31.78,0:24:33.22,Default,,0,0,0,,reach into your views backing
Dialogue: 0,0:24:33.22,0:24:34.51,Default,,0,0,0,,layer to modify the corner
Dialogue: 0,0:24:34.51,0:24:35.90,Default,,0,0,0,,radius, but as long as you do
Dialogue: 0,0:24:35.90,0:24:37.22,Default,,0,0,0,,that within an animation block
Dialogue: 0,0:24:37.22,0:24:38.50,Default,,0,0,0,,we're going to implicitly create
Dialogue: 0,0:24:38.50,0:24:39.95,Default,,0,0,0,,that animation for you and it'll
Dialogue: 0,0:24:39.95,0:24:40.91,Default,,0,0,0,,be fully trackable and
Dialogue: 0,0:24:40.91,0:24:41.34,Default,,0,0,0,,scrubbable.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:41.92,0:24:43.11,Default,,0,0,0,,In fact, you can even do this
Dialogue: 0,0:24:43.11,0:24:44.48,Default,,0,0,0,,from the UIView animate method.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:45.93,0:24:46.75,Default,,0,0,0,,So that takes care of our
Dialogue: 0,0:24:46.75,0:24:47.75,Default,,0,0,0,,interactive corner radius
Dialogue: 0,0:24:47.75,0:24:48.30,Default,,0,0,0,,animation.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:48.30,0:24:50.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Now what about these two guys,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:50.82,0:24:52.07,Default,,0,0,0,,we only want to animate the top
Dialogue: 0,0:24:52.07,0:24:53.53,Default,,0,0,0,,left and right corners, so how
Dialogue: 0,0:24:53.53,0:24:54.19,Default,,0,0,0,,do we do that?
Dialogue: 0,0:24:55.79,0:24:56.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Well I'm also happy to let you
Dialogue: 0,0:24:56.76,0:24:57.92,Default,,0,0,0,,guys know we're adding a new
Dialogue: 0,0:24:57.92,0:24:59.51,Default,,0,0,0,,property to CALayer, which is
Dialogue: 0,0:24:59.51,0:24:59.98,Default,,0,0,0,,maskedCorners.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:00.52,0:25:05.56,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:25:06.06,0:25:06.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Now this allows us to
Dialogue: 0,0:25:06.63,0:25:07.80,Default,,0,0,0,,selectively choose which corners
Dialogue: 0,0:25:07.80,0:25:08.93,Default,,0,0,0,,we want to apply our corner
Dialogue: 0,0:25:08.93,0:25:10.36,Default,,0,0,0,,radius mask to, which in our
Dialogue: 0,0:25:10.36,0:25:11.75,Default,,0,0,0,,case is going to be the top left
Dialogue: 0,0:25:11.75,0:25:12.75,Default,,0,0,0,,and top right corners.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:14.91,0:25:16.30,Default,,0,0,0,,And now finally, here's the code
Dialogue: 0,0:25:16.30,0:25:17.63,Default,,0,0,0,,to do this again, omitting some
Dialogue: 0,0:25:17.63,0:25:18.49,Default,,0,0,0,,of the repetitive bits.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:18.80,0:25:20.42,Default,,0,0,0,,So, we're just creating a new
Dialogue: 0,0:25:20.42,0:25:21.34,Default,,0,0,0,,animator here, we're going to
Dialogue: 0,0:25:21.34,0:25:22.53,Default,,0,0,0,,use a linear timing function and
Dialogue: 0,0:25:22.53,0:25:23.61,Default,,0,0,0,,we're going to perform our
Dialogue: 0,0:25:23.61,0:25:25.25,Default,,0,0,0,,corner radius animations and
Dialogue: 0,0:25:25.25,0:25:26.16,Default,,0,0,0,,that's pretty much all we need
Dialogue: 0,0:25:26.26,0:25:28.08,Default,,0,0,0,,to and that gives us the
Dialogue: 0,0:25:28.08,0:25:28.96,Default,,0,0,0,,following animation.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:34.08,0:25:35.16,Default,,0,0,0,,And it's subtle, but we are
Dialogue: 0,0:25:35.16,0:25:36.61,Default,,0,0,0,,indeed interactively scrubbing
Dialogue: 0,0:25:36.61,0:25:37.76,Default,,0,0,0,,the corner radius there, which
Dialogue: 0,0:25:37.76,0:25:38.00,Default,,0,0,0,,is cool.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:42.44,0:25:44.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Now if there's one underlying
Dialogue: 0,0:25:44.58,0:25:46.78,Default,,0,0,0,,message thus far it's that it's
Dialogue: 0,0:25:46.88,0:25:48.46,Default,,0,0,0,,really important for all your
Dialogue: 0,0:25:48.46,0:25:50.08,Default,,0,0,0,,animators to share the same unit
Dialogue: 0,0:25:50.08,0:25:50.58,Default,,0,0,0,,duration.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:51.15,0:25:52.47,Default,,0,0,0,,This makes scrubbing them really
Dialogue: 0,0:25:52.55,0:25:54.05,Default,,0,0,0,,easy and it makes it possible to
Dialogue: 0,0:25:54.05,0:25:55.21,Default,,0,0,0,,uniformly scrub them.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:56.63,0:25:58.41,Default,,0,0,0,,But, you know, sometimes it's
Dialogue: 0,0:25:58.41,0:25:59.27,Default,,0,0,0,,kind of useful to have an
Dialogue: 0,0:25:59.27,0:26:00.65,Default,,0,0,0,,animation that finishes a little
Dialogue: 0,0:26:00.65,0:26:02.16,Default,,0,0,0,,early or one that maybe starts
Dialogue: 0,0:26:02.16,0:26:02.73,Default,,0,0,0,,with a delay.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:03.76,0:26:06.66,Default,,0,0,0,,And an example this could be in
Dialogue: 0,0:26:06.66,0:26:08.40,Default,,0,0,0,,the following animation where if
Dialogue: 0,0:26:08.40,0:26:09.58,Default,,0,0,0,,you notice the Details button
Dialogue: 0,0:26:09.58,0:26:10.81,Default,,0,0,0,,here it animates in about
Dialogue: 0,0:26:10.81,0:26:12.80,Default,,0,0,0,,halfway through is when it
Dialogue: 0,0:26:12.80,0:26:13.24,Default,,0,0,0,,starts.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:13.63,0:26:14.98,Default,,0,0,0,,And it's fully animated out
Dialogue: 0,0:26:14.98,0:26:16.34,Default,,0,0,0,,around that same halfway point.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:17.65,0:26:19.42,Default,,0,0,0,,And if we try this interactively
Dialogue: 0,0:26:19.42,0:26:21.11,Default,,0,0,0,,you can really see it, so it
Dialogue: 0,0:26:21.11,0:26:22.32,Default,,0,0,0,,just starts animating at this
Dialogue: 0,0:26:22.32,0:26:25.50,Default,,0,0,0,,point and it's fully animated
Dialogue: 0,0:26:25.50,0:26:26.62,Default,,0,0,0,,out right around there.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:27.70,0:26:29.47,Default,,0,0,0,,And if you look across UIKit you
Dialogue: 0,0:26:29.47,0:26:30.93,Default,,0,0,0,,can actually see a lot of places
Dialogue: 0,0:26:30.93,0:26:31.75,Default,,0,0,0,,where we do this.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:31.99,0:26:34.12,Default,,0,0,0,,In fact, UINavigationBar since
Dialogue: 0,0:26:34.22,0:26:36.07,Default,,0,0,0,,iOS 7 has had this effect when
Dialogue: 0,0:26:36.07,0:26:37.63,Default,,0,0,0,,you drive that animation
Dialogue: 0,0:26:37.63,0:26:38.27,Default,,0,0,0,,interactively.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:40.12,0:26:41.68,Default,,0,0,0,,So, we could create an animator
Dialogue: 0,0:26:41.68,0:26:43.24,Default,,0,0,0,,with reduced duration or we
Dialogue: 0,0:26:43.24,0:26:44.47,Default,,0,0,0,,could use a delay factor here,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:44.85,0:26:45.57,Default,,0,0,0,,but that's really going to
Dialogue: 0,0:26:45.57,0:26:46.79,Default,,0,0,0,,complicate our scrubbing code.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:47.18,0:26:48.67,Default,,0,0,0,,It turns out there's a much more
Dialogue: 0,0:26:48.67,0:26:49.86,Default,,0,0,0,,elegant solution here and that
Dialogue: 0,0:26:49.86,0:26:51.71,Default,,0,0,0,,is using keyframe animations.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:52.78,0:26:54.23,Default,,0,0,0,,So, if we look at the UIView
Dialogue: 0,0:26:54.23,0:26:55.44,Default,,0,0,0,,headers we see the following two
Dialogue: 0,0:26:55.44,0:26:56.26,Default,,0,0,0,,keyframe methods.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:56.96,0:26:57.78,Default,,0,0,0,,And I'd like to draw your
Dialogue: 0,0:26:57.78,0:26:59.34,Default,,0,0,0,,attention to RelativeStartTime
Dialogue: 0,0:26:59.34,0:27:00.51,Default,,0,0,0,,and RelativeDuration.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:01.15,0:27:02.10,Default,,0,0,0,,So, in order to create this
Dialogue: 0,0:27:02.10,0:27:04.55,Default,,0,0,0,,effect, we perform a keyframe
Dialogue: 0,0:27:04.55,0:27:06.17,Default,,0,0,0,,animation inside of our property
Dialogue: 0,0:27:06.17,0:27:07.96,Default,,0,0,0,,animator, so we call
Dialogue: 0,0:27:07.96,0:27:09.79,Default,,0,0,0,,UIView.animateKeyframes with a
Dialogue: 0,0:27:09.79,0:27:11.21,Default,,0,0,0,,relative duration of zero.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:11.73,0:27:12.87,Default,,0,0,0,,And what this means is our
Dialogue: 0,0:27:12.87,0:27:14.36,Default,,0,0,0,,keyframe animation will inherit
Dialogue: 0,0:27:14.52,0:27:15.70,Default,,0,0,0,,the duration of its outer
Dialogue: 0,0:27:15.70,0:27:17.73,Default,,0,0,0,,property animator and in fact,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:17.89,0:27:19.52,Default,,0,0,0,,if you nest animations like this
Dialogue: 0,0:27:19.79,0:27:20.81,Default,,0,0,0,,you'll get this inheritance
Dialogue: 0,0:27:20.81,0:27:21.78,Default,,0,0,0,,behavior for free.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:21.86,0:27:22.94,Default,,0,0,0,,So, this can be really useful if
Dialogue: 0,0:27:22.94,0:27:23.86,Default,,0,0,0,,you're not using property
Dialogue: 0,0:27:23.86,0:27:24.38,Default,,0,0,0,,animators.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:26.28,0:27:27.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Now when we expand our comments
Dialogue: 0,0:27:27.83,0:27:28.98,Default,,0,0,0,,view we want that animation to
Dialogue: 0,0:27:28.98,0:27:29.98,Default,,0,0,0,,start late so we're going to use
Dialogue: 0,0:27:29.98,0:27:32.00,Default,,0,0,0,,a relative start time of 0.5 and
Dialogue: 0,0:27:32.35,0:27:33.29,Default,,0,0,0,,we're going to compensate for
Dialogue: 0,0:27:33.29,0:27:34.14,Default,,0,0,0,,that by using a relative
Dialogue: 0,0:27:34.14,0:27:35.35,Default,,0,0,0,,duration of 0.5.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:35.93,0:27:37.56,Default,,0,0,0,,And when we collapse it we're
Dialogue: 0,0:27:37.56,0:27:38.43,Default,,0,0,0,,going to use a relative start
Dialogue: 0,0:27:38.43,0:27:39.60,Default,,0,0,0,,time of zero because we want it
Dialogue: 0,0:27:39.60,0:27:41.31,Default,,0,0,0,,to immediately begin or we use a
Dialogue: 0,0:27:41.31,0:27:43.97,Default,,0,0,0,,relative duration of 0.5 so that
Dialogue: 0,0:27:43.97,0:27:44.79,Default,,0,0,0,,it finishes early.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:45.71,0:27:46.41,Default,,0,0,0,,And I'd like to draw your
Dialogue: 0,0:27:46.41,0:27:47.42,Default,,0,0,0,,attention to these two
Dialogue: 0,0:27:47.42,0:27:48.18,Default,,0,0,0,,parameters here.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:48.79,0:27:49.79,Default,,0,0,0,,So, you don't have to use a
Dialogue: 0,0:27:49.79,0:27:50.99,Default,,0,0,0,,linear timing function for your
Dialogue: 0,0:27:50.99,0:27:52.80,Default,,0,0,0,,keyframe animations you can use
Dialogue: 0,0:27:52.98,0:27:54.53,Default,,0,0,0,,any timing function you want,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:54.67,0:27:56.18,Default,,0,0,0,,including your own custom timing
Dialogue: 0,0:27:56.18,0:27:56.65,Default,,0,0,0,,functions.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:57.22,0:27:58.19,Default,,0,0,0,,And if you have multiple
Dialogue: 0,0:27:58.19,0:27:59.63,Default,,0,0,0,,keyframes here, which we don't,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:00.08,0:28:01.41,Default,,0,0,0,,you could actually interpolate
Dialogue: 0,0:28:01.45,0:28:02.90,Default,,0,0,0,,them using the options parameter
Dialogue: 0,0:28:03.99,0:28:05.24,Default,,0,0,0,,or control the way that they're
Dialogue: 0,0:28:05.24,0:28:06.47,Default,,0,0,0,,interpolated using the options
Dialogue: 0,0:28:06.47,0:28:06.82,Default,,0,0,0,,parameter.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:06.82,0:28:12.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Now lastly, I'd like to talk a
Dialogue: 0,0:28:12.49,0:28:14.04,Default,,0,0,0,,little bit about additive
Dialogue: 0,0:28:14.04,0:28:14.55,Default,,0,0,0,,animations.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:16.42,0:28:17.46,Default,,0,0,0,,So, additive animations are
Dialogue: 0,0:28:17.46,0:28:19.44,Default,,0,0,0,,really powerful and I find them
Dialogue: 0,0:28:19.44,0:28:20.66,Default,,0,0,0,,really interesting because they
Dialogue: 0,0:28:20.66,0:28:23.23,Default,,0,0,0,,allow us to modify or to animate
Dialogue: 0,0:28:23.23,0:28:25.20,Default,,0,0,0,,a single property of a view with
Dialogue: 0,0:28:25.20,0:28:26.86,Default,,0,0,0,,multiple simultaneously running
Dialogue: 0,0:28:26.96,0:28:27.48,Default,,0,0,0,,animations.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:28.48,0:28:31.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Now for this demonstration the
Dialogue: 0,0:28:32.24,0:28:34.63,Default,,0,0,0,,sort of point of it is that I'd
Dialogue: 0,0:28:34.70,0:28:36.07,Default,,0,0,0,,like to demonstrate how to think
Dialogue: 0,0:28:36.07,0:28:37.35,Default,,0,0,0,,a little bit more additively
Dialogue: 0,0:28:37.42,0:28:38.40,Default,,0,0,0,,when we're designing and
Dialogue: 0,0:28:38.40,0:28:39.32,Default,,0,0,0,,building our animations.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:39.83,0:28:40.50,Default,,0,0,0,,So, let's say that we have a
Dialogue: 0,0:28:40.50,0:28:41.99,Default,,0,0,0,,square and let's say that we'd
Dialogue: 0,0:28:41.99,0:28:43.76,Default,,0,0,0,,like to animate it by 360
Dialogue: 0,0:28:43.76,0:28:44.75,Default,,0,0,0,,degrees times 10.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:45.14,0:28:45.95,Default,,0,0,0,,That animation might look
Dialogue: 0,0:28:45.95,0:28:46.76,Default,,0,0,0,,something like this.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:50.71,0:28:51.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Now you might be thinking well
Dialogue: 0,0:28:51.71,0:28:53.65,Default,,0,0,0,,that's just as easy as animating
Dialogue: 0,0:28:53.65,0:28:56.14,Default,,0,0,0,,the transform our view and you
Dialogue: 0,0:28:56.14,0:28:57.22,Default,,0,0,0,,wouldn't actually be wrong.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:58.40,0:28:59.88,Default,,0,0,0,,But code such as this, which is
Dialogue: 0,0:28:59.88,0:29:01.34,Default,,0,0,0,,animating our view by 20 pi
Dialogue: 0,0:29:01.34,0:29:03.45,Default,,0,0,0,,radians, does not produce that
Dialogue: 0,0:29:03.45,0:29:03.92,Default,,0,0,0,,animation.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:04.93,0:29:06.34,Default,,0,0,0,,It actually produces this
Dialogue: 0,0:29:06.34,0:29:06.77,Default,,0,0,0,,animation.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:07.31,0:29:10.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Did you see it?
Dialogue: 0,0:29:10.68,0:29:14.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, it actually didn't animate
Dialogue: 0,0:29:15.01,0:29:16.35,Default,,0,0,0,,and there's a really good reason
Dialogue: 0,0:29:16.35,0:29:16.70,Default,,0,0,0,,for that.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:17.67,0:29:18.90,Default,,0,0,0,,That's because Core Animation
Dialogue: 0,0:29:18.97,0:29:20.19,Default,,0,0,0,,only cares about the total
Dialogue: 0,0:29:20.19,0:29:21.03,Default,,0,0,0,,displacement when you're
Dialogue: 0,0:29:21.03,0:29:22.26,Default,,0,0,0,,animating the transform of your
Dialogue: 0,0:29:22.26,0:29:22.48,Default,,0,0,0,,view.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:23.27,0:29:25.00,Default,,0,0,0,,So, in this case, the target
Dialogue: 0,0:29:25.00,0:29:26.66,Default,,0,0,0,,rotational value, which is 20 pi
Dialogue: 0,0:29:26.66,0:29:28.41,Default,,0,0,0,,radians, is the same orientation
Dialogue: 0,0:29:28.41,0:29:30.21,Default,,0,0,0,,as the current rotational value.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:30.89,0:29:32.10,Default,,0,0,0,,So, the total displacement there
Dialogue: 0,0:29:32.10,0:29:33.11,Default,,0,0,0,,is actually zero.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:34.50,0:29:35.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Now Core Animation will actually
Dialogue: 0,0:29:36.13,0:29:37.31,Default,,0,0,0,,produce an animation for you,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:37.48,0:29:38.73,Default,,0,0,0,,but it's to and from values are
Dialogue: 0,0:29:38.73,0:29:39.62,Default,,0,0,0,,going to be the same.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:40.74,0:29:42.11,Default,,0,0,0,,And you know a similar problem
Dialogue: 0,0:29:42.11,0:29:43.79,Default,,0,0,0,,exists if you try to rotate a
Dialogue: 0,0:29:43.79,0:29:44.99,Default,,0,0,0,,view by 180 degrees
Dialogue: 0,0:29:45.05,0:29:46.99,Default,,0,0,0,,counterclockwise by specifying
Dialogue: 0,0:29:46.99,0:29:48.05,Default,,0,0,0,,negative pi radians.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:49.07,0:29:50.57,Default,,0,0,0,,And that's because Core
Dialogue: 0,0:29:50.57,0:29:52.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Animation because it only cares
Dialogue: 0,0:29:52.09,0:29:53.87,Default,,0,0,0,,about total displacement is
Dialogue: 0,0:29:53.87,0:29:54.90,Default,,0,0,0,,going to look for the shortest
Dialogue: 0,0:29:55.26,0:29:56.25,Default,,0,0,0,,path, which when ambiguous,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:56.25,0:29:57.56,Default,,0,0,0,,which it is here, will be
Dialogue: 0,0:29:57.73,0:29:58.30,Default,,0,0,0,,clockwise.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:58.30,0:30:00.98,Default,,0,0,0,,So, how do we do this?
Dialogue: 0,0:30:01.09,0:30:03.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Well we could drop down a core
Dialogue: 0,0:30:03.27,0:30:04.60,Default,,0,0,0,,animation and create our own CA
Dialogue: 0,0:30:04.60,0:30:06.49,Default,,0,0,0,,basic animation and manually set
Dialogue: 0,0:30:06.49,0:30:07.57,Default,,0,0,0,,our to and from values and
Dialogue: 0,0:30:07.57,0:30:08.58,Default,,0,0,0,,that's perfectly fine and would
Dialogue: 0,0:30:08.58,0:30:08.83,Default,,0,0,0,,work.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:09.44,0:30:11.61,Default,,0,0,0,,But we wouldn't get the tracking
Dialogue: 0,0:30:11.61,0:30:12.58,Default,,0,0,0,,and scrubbing behavior from
Dialogue: 0,0:30:12.58,0:30:13.50,Default,,0,0,0,,property animators.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:14.14,0:30:15.34,Default,,0,0,0,,And it also would make this
Dialogue: 0,0:30:15.41,0:30:16.84,Default,,0,0,0,,example much less interesting.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:18.34,0:30:20.22,Default,,0,0,0,,What we could do is we could
Dialogue: 0,0:30:20.39,0:30:22.00,Default,,0,0,0,,decompose this into several
Dialogue: 0,0:30:22.00,0:30:23.79,Default,,0,0,0,,smaller additive rotational
Dialogue: 0,0:30:23.83,0:30:25.45,Default,,0,0,0,,animations and animate them all
Dialogue: 0,0:30:25.45,0:30:26.66,Default,,0,0,0,,together to create our desired
Dialogue: 0,0:30:26.66,0:30:27.01,Default,,0,0,0,,effect.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:27.98,0:30:30.17,Default,,0,0,0,,So, it turns out transform is an
Dialogue: 0,0:30:30.17,0:30:31.51,Default,,0,0,0,,additively animatable property
Dialogue: 0,0:30:32.04,0:30:33.54,Default,,0,0,0,,as long as it's affine along
Dialogue: 0,0:30:33.54,0:30:35.24,Default,,0,0,0,,with frame, bound, center, and
Dialogue: 0,0:30:35.24,0:30:35.65,Default,,0,0,0,,position.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:37.60,0:30:39.46,Default,,0,0,0,,So, in our solution we're
Dialogue: 0,0:30:39.46,0:30:40.90,Default,,0,0,0,,actually going to create 20
Dialogue: 0,0:30:41.27,0:30:43.82,Default,,0,0,0,,animations altogether and each
Dialogue: 0,0:30:43.82,0:30:44.96,Default,,0,0,0,,animation is going to animate
Dialogue: 0,0:30:45.03,0:30:47.36,Default,,0,0,0,,for 180 degrees and altogether
Dialogue: 0,0:30:47.36,0:30:49.18,Default,,0,0,0,,they're going to contribute to
Dialogue: 0,0:30:49.18,0:30:50.17,Default,,0,0,0,,this following animation.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:51.89,0:30:53.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Now what's kind of cool is we
Dialogue: 0,0:30:53.14,0:30:55.06,Default,,0,0,0,,actually have 20 animations
Dialogue: 0,0:30:55.20,0:30:56.61,Default,,0,0,0,,running simultaneously here.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:57.59,0:30:58.76,Default,,0,0,0,,And I'm not suggesting that this
Dialogue: 0,0:30:58.76,0:31:02.83,Default,,0,0,0,,is a good idea generally, but it
Dialogue: 0,0:31:02.92,0:31:04.30,Default,,0,0,0,,does help us think a little bit
Dialogue: 0,0:31:04.30,0:31:06.15,Default,,0,0,0,,more additively when we're
Dialogue: 0,0:31:06.50,0:31:07.94,Default,,0,0,0,,designing and composing and
Dialogue: 0,0:31:07.94,0:31:09.00,Default,,0,0,0,,creating our animations.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:09.05,0:31:10.55,Default,,0,0,0,,So, the point of this is to
Dialogue: 0,0:31:10.82,0:31:12.45,Default,,0,0,0,,consider how you can chain many
Dialogue: 0,0:31:12.45,0:31:14.81,Default,,0,0,0,,animations together or compose
Dialogue: 0,0:31:14.81,0:31:16.26,Default,,0,0,0,,together to create interesting
Dialogue: 0,0:31:16.26,0:31:16.91,Default,,0,0,0,,transitions.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:18.62,0:31:21.30,Default,,0,0,0,,So today, we learned about how
Dialogue: 0,0:31:21.30,0:31:22.32,Default,,0,0,0,,to make animations fully
Dialogue: 0,0:31:22.32,0:31:23.60,Default,,0,0,0,,interactive and interruptible
Dialogue: 0,0:31:23.60,0:31:24.75,Default,,0,0,0,,using some modern techniques.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:25.70,0:31:26.75,Default,,0,0,0,,We also talked about how to
Dialogue: 0,0:31:26.75,0:31:28.17,Default,,0,0,0,,coordinate several animations
Dialogue: 0,0:31:28.17,0:31:29.82,Default,,0,0,0,,together that all have unique
Dialogue: 0,0:31:29.92,0:31:30.70,Default,,0,0,0,,timing functions.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:31.45,0:31:33.23,Default,,0,0,0,,And we looked at some techniques
Dialogue: 0,0:31:33.23,0:31:34.76,Default,,0,0,0,,in order to help us create some
Dialogue: 0,0:31:34.76,0:31:36.07,Default,,0,0,0,,really awesome animations for
Dialogue: 0,0:31:36.07,0:31:36.55,Default,,0,0,0,,our users.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:37.27,0:31:38.72,Default,,0,0,0,,It is my hope that you walk away
Dialogue: 0,0:31:38.72,0:31:40.85,Default,,0,0,0,,from this presentation and
Dialogue: 0,0:31:41.05,0:31:42.14,Default,,0,0,0,,consider making more of your
Dialogue: 0,0:31:42.14,0:31:43.36,Default,,0,0,0,,animated transitions fully
Dialogue: 0,0:31:43.36,0:31:44.61,Default,,0,0,0,,interactive and interruptible.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:45.19,0:31:47.20,Default,,0,0,0,,So, we have a few related
Dialogue: 0,0:31:47.20,0:31:47.70,Default,,0,0,0,,sessions.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:47.94,0:31:49.39,Default,,0,0,0,,If you've missed any of these I
Dialogue: 0,0:31:49.39,0:31:50.28,Default,,0,0,0,,encourage you to watch them
Dialogue: 0,0:31:50.28,0:31:52.73,Default,,0,0,0,,online and there are a few
Dialogue: 0,0:31:52.73,0:31:54.30,Default,,0,0,0,,interesting sessions from prior
Dialogue: 0,0:31:54.30,0:31:54.80,Default,,0,0,0,,years.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:55.07,0:31:56.05,Default,,0,0,0,,So, if you're interested in
Dialogue: 0,0:31:56.05,0:31:57.54,Default,,0,0,0,,animations, I highly encourage
Dialogue: 0,0:31:57.54,0:31:58.37,Default,,0,0,0,,you to check these out,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:58.81,0:32:00.08,Default,,0,0,0,,especially last year's session
Dialogue: 0,0:32:00.08,0:32:00.81,Default,,0,0,0,,where we introduced
